<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Vice-Chairman on Implementing Food Hygiene Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), Wu Jieping,
today called on governments at all levels to put the
implementation of the Food Hygiene Law high on their work agenda.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the call this morning at the 26th session of the 8th
NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said that the progress made so far to carry out the law,
which was passed and went into effect on October 30, 1995 at the
16th session of the 8th NPC Standing Committee, could be viewed as
an important way of measuring whether governments of various
levels really care for the people.
</P>
<P>
The vice-chairman was presenting a report on the work on the
law done by the Standing Committee's law-enforcement inspection
teams.
</P>
<P>
During the April-June period, the NPC Standing Committee
dispatched three inspection teams to over 50 food products
factories and companies in the provinces of Hubei, Hunan, Zhejiang
and Jiangsu, as well as two cities of Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The review covered the manufacturing, processing and management
of food products for the general public as well as food products
for infants.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that since the promulgation of the law, China has made
tremendous achievements in the fields of supervision and
management of food hygiene, with the percentage of certifiably
hygienic food rising steadily.
</P>
<P>
However, the overall situation of food hygiene across the
country still doesn't look good enough, the vice-chairman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Vice-Chairman on Implementing Food Hygiene Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He noted that many Chinese people pay little attention to food
hygiene and do not know how to use the legal system to protect
their own interests and strike out against such unlawful practices
as the manufacturing and selling of fake and sub-standard food.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Health show that the incidence
of intestinal infectious disease resulting from poor food hygiene
in China accounts for over 80 percent of all infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
The vice-chairman urged departments concerned to solve those
food hygiene problems which have a wider social impact and pose a
greater threat to people's health in a planned way, stressing that
priority should be given to the examination of food sold by street
vendors.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the supervision of food hygiene is
comparatively weak in rural areas and outlying areas of cities
which harbor numerous illegally-operating manufacturing plants
that make substandard food products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
