<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Futures Exchange Trades Half-Year Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The London International Financial
Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) traded a total of 100.99
million contracts during the first half of this year, a rise of 22
percent over the same 1996 period, hitting an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released today showed that the LIFFE saw its busiest
June ever, trading a record of 17,044,483 futures and options
contracts, 35 percent up on June 1996. Average daily volume
amounted to 811,642 contracts, representing a daily nominal
turnover of 166 billion pounds (272 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Jack Wigglesworth, chairman of the LIFFE, said, "In this, its
15th anniversary year, LIFFE has set a new half-year volume record
and was the second largest futures and options exchange in the
world for the half-year."
</P>
<P>
"This reflects the market's confidence in the exchange and the
continuing demand by our membership and end-users for the wide
range of products available at LIFFE in the uncertainty
surrounding the advent of Economic and Monetary Union," he added.
</P>
<P>
The LIFFE and the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT) launched their
linkage agreement in May 1997 whereby the 30-year U.S. Treasury
Bond and the German Government Bond (Bund) futures and options
contracts are available for trading at the LIFFE and the CBOT
respectively during European and U.S. business hours. Since then,
the LIFFE has traded a total of 153,651 Bund futures and options
contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
