<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels Move to Rescue Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Chief peace negotiators from both
the Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) would soon have their first face-to-face meeting, TV
monitored here said today.
</P>
<P>
The report said chief government negotiator Fortunato Abat and
MILF vice chairman for political affairs Ghadzali Jaafar were due
to meet in Cotabato City in southern Philippines to revive the
stalled peace talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Bloody clashes between government troops and MILF rebels
erupted after the military launched a war against MILF members in
the second half of June.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least 100 rebels and five soldiers were
killed in the fighting. As a result, the MILF boycotted its sixth
round of low-level peace talks slated for June 29-30 with the
government.
</P>
<P>
A father in a university in Cotabato City has been proposed by
Jaafar as a peace mediator for the two sides. He said the two
chief peace negotiators would discuss a proposed comprehensive
ceasefire, the overall situation in Mindanao and the settlement of
thousands of civilians displaced by the recent clashes.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member rebel group which refused to accept
the peace agreement signed last year between the government and
the Moro National Liberation Front.  
</P>
</TEXT>
