<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Oppositions Launch Protest March in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of five Lesotho
opposition parties today defied a government ban on protest
marches to the Royal Palace in Maseru, capital of the kingdom,
when they led hundreds of supporters to the Office of King Letsie
III, reported the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
The protest, organised by the Basotho National Party and
supported by other leading opposition groups, was the latest in a
series of demonstrations against the government of Prime Minister
Ntsu Mokhehle, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The protesters presented a petition to the King's private
secretary Mabote Lerothodi, who promised to pass it on to the
head of state.
</P>
<P>
The petition said Mokhehle's establishment of the Lesotho
Congress for Democracy (LCD) and his installation of the LCD as
the new governing party were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Mokhehle resigned as leader of the ruling
Basutoland Congress Party and formed a new party, the LCD, to
which he transferred governance immediately following its
installation.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle's political moves were rejected by a coalition of
opposition parties, vowing to launch a series of protesting actions to
make Lesotho ungovernable and parliament unworkable.
</P>
<P>
In the petition, the oppositions once again called on the King
to dissolve Mokhehle's administration and appoint an interim
government to ensure the democratic rule in the small land-locked
kingdom surrounded by South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
