<HEADLINE> EC Repeats Ban on British Beef Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC) today
repeated its ban on British beef exports after the country
allegedly exported more than 1,000 tons of beef to various nations.
</P>
<P>
An EC spokesman said today an EC inspection team at work in
Britain has verified suspicions that Britain fraudulently exported
its beef to many countries in defiance of an European Union
embargo imposed in March 1996 amid fears of "mad cow" disease.
</P>
<P>
Emma Bonino, the EU commissioner responsible for consumer
policy, has informed the British government of the inspection
team's findings and blamed the manifest inefficiency of British
checking mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The commission, which refused to disclose the findings, is
contacting nations which have imported British beef in a bid to
help them deal with beef smuggled from Britain.
</P>
<P>
It is also discussing whether to punish Britain because of its
inefficient checking mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The French weekly "Le Canard Enchaine" Wednesday reported that
the international police force Interpol had began an investigation
of illegally exported beef via Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The weekly cited an Interpol telex as saying that British
soldiers were involved in beef smuggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
