<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Widow of Deng Xiaoping to Rousing Welcome in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- At the Hong Kong handover
ceremony, a respectable woman with greying hair in her 80s came
to the fore among emissaries, both Chinese and foreign. Her name
was Zhuo Lin, widow of the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Deng said on a number of occasions that he wished to take a
trip to Hong Kong after its return to the motherland. "I very much
want to take a short walk and stay just for a while even if I'm in
a wheelchair," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
But Deng, the founder of "one country, two systems" concept,
passed away at the age of 93 in late February before his ardent
aspiration comes true. However, it was Deng who announced to the
world China's firm belief to resume its exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong 18 years ago, and included the concept of "one
country two systems" into the annals of history.
His concept eventually led to Hong Kong's return to China on July
1 while maintaining its capitalist system and way of life,
</P>
<P>
"I have make this trip on behalf of Xiaoping," said Zhuo Lin,
who is here with her children for Hong Kong's handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
As part of her preparations for her trip and make it more
meaningful, Madame Zhuo Lin bought a Hong Kong atlas and read it
repeatedly with great care. She strove to acquaint herself with
this part of the Chinese territory, which had been under the
British colonial rule for 156 years. "It is a great red-letter
event for the entire Chinese nation to resume its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong and I sincerely hope that the future
for Hong Kong will be still more splendid," she said.
</P>
<P>
As the five-star national flag rose side by side with regional
bauhinia flag of the Hong Kong SAR at zero hour on July 1, Madame
Zhuo and her children moved to tears. For Zhuo lin, she could
hardly control herself and all sorts of feelings welled up in her
heart.
</P>
<P>
At the inaugural ceremony for the establishment of the HKSAR
government at 10 sharp am on July 1, President Jiang Zemin
descended the rostrum especially to greet and shook hands with
smiling Zhuo, who was then seated at the second row of the rostrum
.
</P>
<P>
During his address at the inaugural ceremony, Tung Chee Hwa,
who was just sworn in as the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong SAR,
said with excitement, "I'm very glad that Madame Zhuo has come,
and we would like to extend her our full and special respect."
</P>
<P>
At Tung's proposal, the entire hall of the inaugural ceremony
burst into rousing applauses. Zhuo Lin rose and made several bows
to the audience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
