<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ulster Loyalists Threaten Murder If March Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Loyalist Volunteer Force (LVF),
an outlawed Protestant guerrilla group, today threatened to kill
Irish Catholic civilians if Britain bans a controversial
Protestant parade in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The LVF said in a telephoned statement to Downtown radio
station near Belfast that it would carry out the murders if the
parade of the ancient Orange Order, scheduled for next Sunday, is
barred from going on through the Garvahgy Road in the Catholic
town of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
"If the Orange parade does not go down the Garvaghy Road on
Sunday, the Irish government may expect civilians to be killed in
the Irish Republic," LVF said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"This threat will be carried out immediately if the parade is
banned," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The LVF was banned last month by the British government on
suspicion of carrying out bombings and shootings.
</P>
<P>
Catholic residents, who favor the independence of Northern
Ireland from the British rule, said they are against the annual
parade because they feel intimidated by the Orange Order.
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order, an exclusively Protestant brotherhood which
holds hundreds of processions across the province each summer, is
a lawful body which condemns violence.
</P>
<P>
Last year's parade turned into a bloody clash between the
Protestants and the Catholics. The British government has recently
vowed to guard against the repeat of last year's violence.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both Protestants and Catholics met last
week to seek ways easing tension in the march season but they
failed to reach an agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
