<HEADLINE> Arafat to Hold Talks with Mubarak on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat will meet with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak Thursday to discuss the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian MENA news agency reported today that Arafat will
arrive here later today for the consultations with Mubarak,
following brief visits to Tunisia and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had held talks with Tunisian and Algerian top leaders on
the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations that collapsed in March after
Israel broke ground for a new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Zohdi al-Keddrah, Palestinian ambassador to Egypt, said that
Arafat and Mubarak will explore the latest developments of the
paralysed Mideast peace process, Israeli intransigence and its
insistence on going ahead with settlement construction.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will also focus on the volatile conditions inside
the occupied Arab territories, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Egyptian efforts are continuing to patch up the peace-making
process and they are highly appreciated by the Palestinian
leadership and people," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stepped in as the main mediator between the
Palestinians and Israelis over the past few weeks as a result of
what many Arabs perceive as a lack of U.S. interest in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak had sent his senior advisor Osama el-Baz to shuttle
between the two sides several times in a bid to bring them back to
the negotiating table. But their gap persists.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said Tuesday that he hoped the
Palestinians and Israelis can conclude something within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, in an interview with the French newspaper "Le Monde"
today, accused Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu of
blowing up the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called upon the U.S. to shoulder its political and moral
responsibilities to force Israel to abide by the signed agreements
and urged France and Europe to contribute to salvaging the
stalled peace process. 
</P>
