<HEADLINE> Onassis International Prizes'97 Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Six people and one U.N. body will
be awarded the Onassis international prizes for 1997, the
organizers of the foundation announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze won "the
Onassis Prize for International Understanding and Social
Achievement."
</P>
<P>
Sir Steven Runciman and Mrs. Dolly Goulandris will be awarded the
prize for culture (Arts and Humanities).
</P>
<P>
The International Maritime Organization, the U.N. agency
responsible for maritime safety and the protection of the marine
environment from pollution by ships, will be granted the prize
for the environment.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Manjula Padmanabhan of India won the top prize in the
Onassis International Cultural Competitions for Theatrical Plays
for "Harvest", followed by Dr. Anton Juan of the Philippines for
"Princess of the Lizard Moon," and Mr. Nagle Jackson of the United
States for "the Elevation of Thieves."
</P>
<P>
The prizes, awarded every two years to international
personalities from politics, art and the environmental movement,
were launched by the late shipping tycoon Aristotle Onassis in
memory of his son Alexander, who died in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
Past recepients of the awards include former U.N. Secretary General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali, U.S. actress Elizabeth Taylor, South
African Bishop Desmond Tutu, theater director Peter Brook and the
human rights organization Amnesty International and
environmentalist Greenpeace organizations.
</P>
<P>
The prizes, ranging from 150,000 to 250,000 U.S. dollars will
be formally awarded by Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos on
September 16 at the Athens Concert Hall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Panel Discusses Economic Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic and
Social Council (ECOSOC) had a discussion about benefits and
drawbacks of the economic globalization at a high-level panel here
today.
</P>
<P>
Heads from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World
Trade Organization (WTO), the United Nations Conference on Trade
and Development (UNCTAD) and the World Bank made statements at the
panel on important developments in the world economy and
international economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, Managing Director of the IMF, said that
globalization and its attendant availability of massive amounts of
private capital had opened new opportunities for investment and
growth in an ever larger number of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
But it had also brought new problems, such as the ignorance of
the less developed countries by the markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus stressed the importance of macroeconomic
stabilization, and of the trade liberalization, price reform,
privatization and other reforms which make stabilization possible.
</P>
<P>
Renato Ruggiero, Director-General of WTO, said that more needed
to be done to help the least-developed countries in relation to
the effects of globalization and the multilateral trading system.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that more than 50 percent of the world's
population had less than five percent of global income. He told
the panel that WTO members had responded by adopting a Plan of
Action for the Least-Developed Countries, a major objective which
was to ensure that all such countries had a strong voice in the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
Rubens Ricupero, Secretary-General of UNCTAD, warned in his
statement a backlash that would jeopardize recent economic reforms
in both developed and developing countries due to increasing
inequality between them.
</P>
<P>
Practically all developing countries were inadequately prepared
for globalization, he said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Jean-Francois Rischard, Vice-president of Finance
and Private-sector Development of the World Bank, said that the
World Bank tried to help countries get their "enabling
environments" right in the context of the new world economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Government Crisis Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The government crisis in
Israel continued as Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu failed to
patch up his feud with Foreign Minister David Levy in their
meeting today.
</P>
<P>
This was the third meeting between the two in the past week
aimed at finding a solution to the crisis caused by Levy's
complaints about his exclusion from the government
decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was originally scheduled on Sunday, but Levy
angrily canceled it after local media exposed that National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon held a secret meeting with
Palestinian Authority (PA) deputy Chairman Mahmoud Abbas (Abu
Mazen) on June 16 without his knowledge. Levy threatened to
resign, a move that could bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after today's meeting at Netanyahu's office in the
Knesset (Parliament), Levy described it as a "serious and
responsible" discussion on all issues. He said he had aired
his position regarding his future role in the cabinet, but
adding nothing had been finalized.
</P>
<P>
Levy did not disclose details of his demands made during
the meeting, but he reportedly told Netanyahu that he must
be the No. 1 person in charge of the foreign affairs and
talks with the Palestinians. Meanwhile, his Gesher Party
demanded more funds on social welfare from the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Gesher's lawmaker Michael Cleiner warned that Levy was still
considering resignation because of the failure of today's
meeting. He said Netanyahu must crystallize the autonomy of
the Foreign Ministry, which often complains about the takeover
of its responsibility by the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Levy apparently also failed to solve their
differences over the dissolution of the so-called inner security
cabinet, or Ketchen cabinet, which now included Netanyahu, Levy
and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
In his plan to reshuffle the cabinet following the Bar-On
scandal not long ago, Netanyahu wanted to transfer Sharon from the
 Infrastructure Ministry to the finance portfolio. But Sharon
conditioned the transfer on his inclusion into the inner cabinet
in order to have a bigger say in the decision-making.
</P>
<P>
Levy, worried about the possible takeover by Sharon of his
position in charge of the peace talks, strongly opposes Sharon's
inclusion and demands the dissolution of the inner cabinet.
</P>
<P>
If Levy resigns, the Netanyahu government is unlikely to
continue because it could lose its majority in the 120-seat
Knesset. The Gesher Party has boasted five of the 66 seats in the
coalition, which has already been plagued by several important
resignations.
</P>
<P>
Former Science Minister Benny Begin resigned in January to
protest the signing of the agreement on Israeli troop
redeployment in Hebron, and Dan Meridor resigned as the Finance
Minister last month due to his rift with Netanyahu in policies.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, the government will step down if it
loses the 61 majority in the Knesset to pave the way for
new elections for both the prime minister and the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leading opposition parties Labor and Meretz wasted
no time in intensifying its campaign to topple the Netanyahu
government. They accused the government of being preoccupied
with "childish" debate on the dissolution of inner cabinet at
a time when Israeli soldiers and Palestinians clashed in
Hebron and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Meretz decided today to table two no-confidence
motions in Netanyahu over the current explosive security
situation in the Palestinian territories. The Knesset is to vote
on the motions early next week and the Netanyahu government is
facing another tough challenge of survival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
