<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-02 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gaps between Greek, Turkish Cypriots Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Gustave Feissel, UN resident
representative in Cyprus, admitted here today that big differences
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides remain in a number of
important issues.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the local press, Feissel explained that major
differences exist in issues such as the future federal executive,
how the federal government takes decisions, sovereignty, security,
territory and displaced persons and property claims as well as
Cyprus' European orientation.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is also divergence of views on the basic
freedoms of settlement and the right to property, while their
positions on freedom of movement do not seem to be too far apart.
</P>
<P>
Feissel made the statement just a week before the
U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot leaders, due to take place from July 9-13 at a rural
retreat called Troutbeck, 145 kilometers north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
He denied the existence of a reported document which
U.N. Secretary-General's special representative for Cyprus, Diego
Cordovez, will submit to both sides at the beginning of the New
York face-to-face talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that at the first closed meeting July 9 with the
leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities, Cordovez
intends to make "an oral presentation of his thoughts which will
be designed to help launch the discussions."
</P>
<P>
Cordovez intends to give President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash the talking points on his
presentation, the UN official added, underlining that the
U.N. goal is to "help the talks out of a possible impasse and act
as facilitator" to the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Denktash threatened Tuesday that he will not attend the
upcoming direct talks if he is not informed of the reported
document beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez, former foreign minister of Ecuador, was appointed as
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special envoy for Cyprus
earlier this year. He will be in New York early next week for
preliminary contact with Feissel ahead of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Annan will open the talks on July 9 with a statement and then
negotiations will be conducted behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
Greece will be represented by its former ambassador to Cyprus,
Alexandros Sandis, and Turkey by Inal Batu, alternate deputy
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Five permanent members of UN Security Council and the European
Union will also send their representatives to the wings of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash held two informal meetings in Nicosia in
October 1994 under the U.N. auspices, which ended in
deadlock. They have not met ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0029 </DOCNO>
