<HEADLINE> Blair Asks for Strict Observation of Hong Kong Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said today his country was determined to ensure that the 1984
Sino-British Joint Declaration is strictly observed.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interests of Britain, of China and the people of
Hong Kong that we make sure the joint declaration is kept to
strictly, and we will, and secondly that we build upon that a
strong and good relation with China for the future, and we will do
that too," Blair said in a speech to parliament.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said it was vital Britain use the Joint
Declaration on how Hong Kong is governed for the next 50 years to
develop relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Under the Joint Declaration, Britain handed Hong Kong back to
China on June 30 after 156 years of colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
"The basis of a strong and stable relationship with China,
which we want, is adherence to the Joint Declaration," said Blair,
who returned Tuesday from Hong Kong where he attended the handover
ceremony and met with Chinese President Jiang Zeming.
</P>
<P>
"That is the basis of the freedoms of the people in Hong Kong,
and that is the basis which we will expect to be adhered to," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
