<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Yemen to Solve Border Dispute Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Saudi and Yemeni officials
will hold talks soon to solve their 60-year old border dispute,
according to reports from Saudi capital city of Riyadh today.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayif Bin Abdel Al-Aziz made the
statement last night after his return from two-day official visit
to Yemen, according to Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that the border dispute between his country and Yemen
might be solved once and for all in the near future.
</P>
<P>
He said Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh told him while he
was staying in Yemeni capital of Sanaa that "we will arrive at a
final solution in the coming days or weeks" to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Saleh wrote a reply letter to the Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul
Aziz pointing out "the gap has been bridged to a larger extent,
we have only little more to go."
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince also delivered a message from King Fahd
to President Saleh dealing with negotiations between the two
countries on the border demarcation and issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni President Saleh paid in early February his second visit
to Saudi Arabia in two years to discuss issues of border
demarcation between the two countries and hold talks with the
Saudi leaders on bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had been locked in border disputes since
1934, but in February 1995 when a Memorandum of Understanding
concerning the solution of the border issues was concluded
between them, tensions were eased and bilateral ties have been
improving.
</P>
<P>
Border demarcation negotiations have been conducted through
joint committees formed in accordance with the Memorandum of
Understanding which defines the basis for ending the border
dispute between the two Arab neighbors on the Arab peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said in a statement at the beginning of this year
that although the border question remains one of the "most
complicated issues in the region, we are confident the two
countries' leadership would overcome all pending issues in a
brotherly spirit."
</P>
<P>
According to the Saudi prince, officials of the two countries
would also discuss soon the activation of the security accord
signed between the two countries last year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement which was signed in July 1996 stipulated that the
two countries would work together to fight drugs smuggling,
terrorism and infiltration and to extradite criminals. The pact
would serve the security interests of both countries as they
share large areas of land and marine borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
