<HEADLINE> Russia Reiterates Support to Solving Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia today reiterated its
readiness to offer support to the UN effort for a Cyprus
settlement and hoped the preliminary work done so far would help
lead to necessary compromise solutions.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Russian Embassy here today said
Russia hopes that the serious approach of the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides, as described in June's U.N. Security Council
resolution, would help reach the goal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution reaffirms its position that a Cyprus
settlement must be based on a state of Cyprus with a single
sovereignty and international personality, and a single
citizenship, with its independence and territorial integrity
safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
It also notes that the state of Cyprus will comprise two
politically equal communities in a bicommunal and bizonal
federation, and that such a settlement must exclude union in whole
or in part with any other country or any form of partition of
secession.
</P>
<P>
This island state has been divided since 1974 when Turkish
troops occupied its northern third in the wake of a short-lived
Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Russian statement considered particularly important the
call on the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities
to cooperate actively and constructively with the U.N.
Secretary-General at next week's direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations between Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides are due to take place from July 9 to 13, at
a rural retreat called Troutbeck, 145 kilometers north of New
York City.
</P>
<P>
The interest of the international community in achieving
progress toward a Cyprus settlement is proved by the dispatch of
special envoys from twelve states and the European Union to New
York to work on the outer circle of the talks, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Russia will be represented to the talks by Vladimir Tchizhov,
head of the Third Directorate for European Affairs of the Russian
Foreign Ministry, according to the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
