<HEADLINE> Train Collision Forces Evacuations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 residents forced
from their homes after two Union Pacific freight trains collided
in eastern Kansas of the United States have returned home.
</P>
<P>
Authorities ordered the evacuations as a precaution after
several derailed freight cars caught fire, sending chlorine gas
leaking into the air.
</P>
<P>
The collision took place before dawn near Rossville, about 15
miles northwest of Topeka, Kansas, sending about 20 freight cars
off the tracks and starting a fire, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Several of the cars carried chemicals and other hazardous
materials.
</P>
<P>
The engineer of one train was killed and a conductor injured.
</P>
<P>
A sheriff's spokeswoman said more than 1,000 residents of
Rossville, including 80 elderly nursing home patients, were
evacuated as a precaution, but none was hurt. 
</P>
