<HEADLINE> Northern Cyprus Head to Meet Turkish Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Northern Cyprus leader Rauf Denktas
will pay a one-day visit to Turkey Friday for a meeting with
Turkish leaders on the Cyprus issue, the Turkish Foreign Ministry
said today.
</P>
<P>
It said Denktas will hold talks with Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel, Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, Deputy Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit, Foreign Minister Ismail Cem as well as State Minister
Sukru Gurel, who is responsible for the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement is expected to be issued before Denktas
returns to the northern part of the divided Cyprus island Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
Denktas' Ankara visit comes a week before UN-brokered direct
talks between Denktas and Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, which
is scheduled on July 9-13.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry issued on Tuesday a statement
declaring that Turkey supported the proposed face-to-face talks,
but warned against "external pressures."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that any settlement to the Cyprus problem
can only be achieved through the free will of both sides. It
condemned the Cypriot military build-up on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
In a clear deviation from the Cyprus policy of the previous
governments, the statement emphasized that Turkey was concerned
about the security of Turkish Cypriots but Cyprus was also
important for the security of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
control of the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side unilaterally declared a breakaway
state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in November 1993,
which was recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktas held two informal meetings in Nicosia in
October 1994 under the U.N. auspices, which ended in
deadlock. They have not met ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
