<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Labor Government Unveils RadicaL Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Gordon Brown, the British chancellor
of exchequer, unveiled today a tax-raising budget designed to cool
the over-heated economy, boost investment and phase out the
government's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Brown told the House of Commons that the main theme of the
first budget by a Labor government in nearly two decades was to
provide "stability, investment, work and opportunity for all."
</P>
<P>
The chancellor promised 3.5 billion pounds (5.6 billion US
dollars) for his Welfare-to-Work scheme to get young people out of
benefit and into jobs.
</P>
<P>
Brown confirmed that he was imposing a windfall tax of 5.2
billion pounds (8.32 billion US dollars) on the excess profits of
utilities that Labor believes were privatized too cheaply by the
previous Conservative government.
</P>
<P>
He said the controversial tax would be used to finance a deal
for 250,000 young jobless by offering them a "ladder of
opportunity" into work.
</P>
<P>
Warning that rapid consumer spending risked sparking an
unsustainable boom, Brown said he would raise an extra 5.5 billion
pounds (9.1 billion US dollars) in tax this year and 4.75 billion
pounds (7.5 billion US dollars) next year to put Britain on the
road to long-term financial stability.
</P>
<P>
On Britain's poor investment record, which the chancellor said
had lagged that of its main competitors since 1980, Brown cut the
main rate of tax on company profits from 33 percent to a record
low of 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
As far as small business, which Brown said would be the main
engine of job creation, are concerned, the chancellor also cut the
tax rate on small companies to 21 percent from 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the purpose of encouraging firms to plough more profits
back into investment instead of paying them out in dividends,
Brown also said he was abolishing tax credits paid to pension
funds, estimated to be worth more than 3 billion pounds (4.8
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The chancellor's budget speech was delayed by up to half an
hour owing to a question from shadow chancellor Peter Lilley's
complaint of Budget leaks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
