<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Leaves Short-Term Interest Rates Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
policy-makers decided today to keep the short-term interest rates
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Fed announced that it had adjourned a two-day meeting of
its policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee and had nothing
further to say. The statement means that the U.S. central bank
left the benchmark federal funds rate on overnight loans between
banks at 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decision has been widely expected in advance by many
economists although some believed a modest increase in short-term
rates would do little harm and would help prevent inflation from
accelerating later this year and next.
</P>
<P>
The Fed made the decision at a time when the U.S. economy has
slowed down sharply from the quick 5.9 percent growth rate in the
first quarter of this year while the inflation was being kept in
low level. Nearly everything fell into place to buy Fed's
policy-makers time to watch and wait.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in the country has decelerated even though the
economy expanded at the fastest pace in nearly a decade and
unemployment dropped to 4.8 percent in May, nearly a 24-year low.
</P>
<P>
Falling energy prices held consumer inflation to a scant 1.4
percent annual rate during the first five months of this year,
down from 3.3 percent for all of last year. Even stripping out
volatile food and energy costs, the inflation rate is just 2.6
percent so far this year, the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
A variety of statistics, most notably retail sales, suggest
that U.S. economic growth in the April-June quarter slowed sharply
to around a 2 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
Still, some economists have cautioned the U.S. Fed that now is
no time for complacency about inflation and that growth will
rebound in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
But other analysts believe that the second-half bounce-back in
the U.S. won't be strong enough to aggravate price pressures and
see little need for higher rates.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed raised the federal fund rate on March 25, the
first time in two years, and left the rate unchanged in its May 20
policy-making meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Approves 115 Mln Dlrs for Brazil Highway Improvements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of a 115 million U.S.
dollar loan to the state of Ceara, Brazil, to help finance
multiple highway improvements.
</P>
<P>
The works of the project include converting 52 km of access
roads to metropolitan Fortaleza into a four-lane, divided roadway
with a bikeway and sidewalks along the entire length.
</P>
<P>
Some 420 km of highways will receive conventional paving and
another 450 km low-cost paving to assure all weather access to
municipal seats.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 510 km of road will be rehabilitated and improved,
with sealing and small works on another 350 km of road.
</P>
<P>
The program will shorten travel times between Ceara's main
production centers and expedite the supply of agricultural and
industrial products to the state and national markets. The state's
tourism industry and competitiveness in world markets will also be
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The IDB loan will also assist the Department of Buildings,
Highways and Transportation in consolidating a modern approach to
road administration and planning.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 250 million dollars. The
local counterpart will contribute 115 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
