<HEADLINE> Kenya to Host Sub-regional Summit on Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A summit meeting of the
Inter-governmental Authority on Development (iGAD) is scheduled
to be open here on July 8 to solve the crisis in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
A Kenyan governmental official said that the two-day summit to
be hosted by IGAD Chairman, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
would also cover Sudan's relations with neighbouring Eritrea,
Ethiopia and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, peace talks weres held in Kenya between
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Sudanese President Hassan
el Bashir to iron out their long-standing differences.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued after the peace talks, the two
presidents requested President Moi to convene a IGAD summit to
pursue the course of peace in southern Sudan and in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
In southern Sudan, the Sudan People's Liberation Army led by
John Garang has fought since 1983 for greater autonomy of the
Christian south from the Moslem north.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan Minister for Environment and Natural
Resources Henry Kosgey today called on IGAD member states to
strengthen the organization's financial base in a bid to
undertake peace initiatives in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The minister said at the on-going session of IGAD Committee of
Experts here that efforts must be made in order to ensure funding
for all the identified programs as IGAD's mandate has been
expanded to covering food security, environment, infrastructure
development and conflict prevention, management and resolution.
</P>
