<HEADLINE> Clinton to Press Allies to Accept Three New NATO Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will
resist pressure from its allies to invite more than three
countries to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
when he attend the Madrid summit next week.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will leave late on Friday for Spain to attend the
special summit of the alliance, scheduled on July 8-9.
</P>
<P>
He has already declared publicly that he wants NATO to extend
membership only to Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic. But
France and Italy are pressing the alliance also to invite Romania
and Slovenia during the summit.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, White House National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger said, "I would think there'd be some lively
discussion of this (at the summit) but at the end of the day... I
think it's fair to say that there will be a consensus on the
three."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the admitting Romania and Slovenia, Berger
said, "The answer is not no, but no at this time."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the summit, Berger said Clinton's view "is that
America must remain anchored in Europe, that NATO was the most
important vehicle of that anchoring."
</P>
<P>
Clinton wanted to "recreate and adapt NATO for a new era in
order for it to be relevant for the American people and relevant
for the security threats that we faced," Berger added.
</P>
<P>
Following the summit, Clinton was expected to visit Poland,
Romania and Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
