<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tea Production Expected to Decline in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The world tea production for 1997
is expected to decline and consumers will face higher tea prices,
said a U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in Sri Lanka and in most tea producing
countries of Africa, extremely dry weather is adversely affecting
tea growing.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that as one of the major tea producing
countries, Kenya's tea output in the first quarter is about
37 percent lower than in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to FAO, world tea production reached a record 2.69
million tons last year, 3 percent increase compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, tea production increased in almost all major tea
producing countries.
</P>
<P>
In India, tea production increased by 4 percent to set a new
record of 778,900 tons while in Africa, Uganda reported an
increase of 26 percent, Malawi 8 percent and Zimbabwe 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In spite of a record harvest, exports from India declined by 6
percent to 154,000 tons due to rising domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
Total tea imports by developed countries rose by nearly 5
percent in 1996 to 612,800 tons while total imports by developing
countries rose from 484,300 tons to 495,800 tons last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
