<HEADLINE> Schneider Admits Fraud in Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Former real estate tycoon Juergen
Schneider today admitted in trial that he had cheated loans of
banks before the collapse of his multi-billion dollar company in
1994, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
But as on Monday when the trial began in a Frankfurt court, he
again tried to make the banks bear some of the blame in accepting
faked documents he presented to seek loans.
</P>
<P>
Schneider, 63, is tried on three charges of serious fraud and
two charges of credit fraud in five real estate projects in
Berlin, Leipzig and Frankfurt, which were linked with the collapse
of his company -- the biggest real estate bankruptcy scandal in
post-war Germany.
</P>
<P>
The trial is expected to last until mid-September and will has
its third session on July 8.
</P>
<P>
In his testimony today, Schneider said the banks had
"generously accepted" the fraudulent documents he presented in
seeking loans. The banks knew about the faked documents and he had
used middlemen in borrowing money, he said.
</P>
<P>
Schneider also denied that his creditors -- some 50 banks --
had been damaged to the extent charged.
</P>
<P>
When Schneider and his wife Claudia suddenly went missing in
April 1994, they left behind a company 5.4 billion marks (3.2
billion US dollars) in debts.
</P>
<P>
The pair were found living in Florida, the United States, 13
months later and were extradited to Germany in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition, separate proceedings were set later on for the
Schneiders on a charge of fraudulent bankruptcy involving about
245 million marks (145 million dollars) which they allegedly
diverted to Switzerland for their escape.
</P>
<P>
Schneider began his business in real estate in 1981. In the
prime of his career, he was involved in prime-location projects in
14 cities, building luxury hotels, office buildings and shopping
arcades. His company based near Frankfurt once owned 168 real
estate properties.
</P>
<P>
Most of these assets have been sold off, still leaving 2.6
billion mark (1.534 billion dollar) debts uncovered. It was
reported that the chief creditor Deutsche Bank had some 1.2
billion marks (708 million dollars) in loan to Schneider when
Schneider's company collapsed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
