<HEADLINE> Higher Inflation for June Expected in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Inflation for June in the
Philippines would be higher than last month's 4.2 percent, which
was the lowest in 10 years, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Economic Development Cielito Habito said the
inflation rate was expected to rise during the month due to higher
spending brought about by the opening of schools.
</P>
<P>
He did not explain further whether food prices had any effects
on the expected higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
However, the month-to-month inflation would again start going
down during the second half of the year due to higher bases in the
third and fourth quarters last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The slightly higher inflation target for June is still within
the 6.4 percent target for the month, Habito said.
</P>
<P>
He added that this would not also distort the country's
inflation target for the full year of 5.2 to 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months of the year, the country's
inflation averaged at 4.6 percent.  
</P>
