<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Rises to 5 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in the
United States bounced to five percent in June after a 24-year low
in May, the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the most dramatic evidence yet that the U.S. economy has
slowed from the quick growth pace of 5.9 percent in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. joblessness rate rose from 4.8 percent in May, the
lowest since late 1973, and 4.9 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The report said U.S. employers added seasonally adjusted
217,000 jobs to their payrolls in June. That was slightly less
than the 236,000 average for the first five months of the year.
</P>
<P>
About 151,000 of the jobs came in private industry. And an
increase of 82,000 state and local government jobs more than
offset a decline of 16,000 federal jobs.
</P>
<P>
Job growth in service industries, particularly health care,
slowed in June, compared with continued strong expansion in
computer services, engineering and management services.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of the slowdown, the average factory workweek
edged down by a tenth of an hour to 41.9 hours. Overtime fell to
4.7 hours. But both remained near historic highs.
</P>
<P>
For whites, the jobless rate rose to 4.2 percent from four
percent in May. For blacks, it edged up to 10.4 percent from 10.3
percent and for Hispanics to 7.6 percent from 7.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
