<HEADLINE> Iraq Asks Russia to Help lift UN Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Speaker Saadoun Hammadi has called upon Russia
to help Iraq get the U.N. sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported today that Hammadi, who
is now leading a delegation on a seven-day visit to Russia, made
this appeal in Moscow Wednesday during a meeting with Russian
First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Hammadi told Nemtsov that Iraq has met all its
commitments to the relevant U.N. resolutions related to the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
He said that now it is incumbent upon the U.N. Security
Council to lift the sanctions imposed on Iraq for its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Russians to talk to the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) on Iraq to report Iraq's full cooperation in disarmament
to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Russian first deputy prime minister described his talks with
Hammadi as "intensive and meaningful."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the INA after the meeting, Nemtsov said
that the Russian government will keep its call to get the
sanctions on Iraq lifted and try to resume the trade and economic
relations between the two countries to the previous level prior
to the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Russian-Iraqi economic ties are "historical"
and the sanctions can not hold up Russian companies from doing
oil business with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under the U.N.-imposed sanctions for nearly
seven years. The sanctions can not be totally lifted before the
UNSCOM in charge of disarming the country releases a report to
certify that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM issues a report on the disarmament every two
months. It has always been accusing Iraq of still hiding a
considerable number of such weapons, which are denied by the
Iraqi government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
