<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Has Service-Oriented Economy: Financial Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economy is a
service-oriented one, Donald Tsang, financial secretary of the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR),
said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition center, Tsang said that the service sector accounts for
over 83 percent of Hong Kong's gross domestic product and over 78
percent of the employment of the region.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the 9th largest service exporter, the largest
container port, the fifth largest center in external banking
transactions and foreign exchange transactions in the world, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Facts show that Hong Kong has a powerful and prosperous
service-oriented economy, and many of its service industries are
internationally competitive, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Also at the briefing, Brian Stevenson, chairman of the Hong
Kong Coalition of Service Industries, outlined the key challenges
facing the service sector in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
To maintain the competitiveness of the service sector, he said,
"We have to make better use of our existing land resources and
premises," to make greater use of technology to improve
efficiency, and to offer better service to customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Service industries should regulate their own operations by
ethical, legal and moral standards, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, to optimize the potential afforded by the development
of the service industries in China's inland areas, "We must look
beyond China to the wider region and the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
At another press conference today, Chau Tak Hay, secretary for
Broadcasting, Culture and Sport, briefed reporters on the radio
and TV sector in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has become the southeast Asian regional headquarters
of many international broadcasters and TV stations, such as the
Cable News Network of the United States and the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the after Hong Kong's return to China, TV
stations in Hong Kong can still retain their English channels, as
a good English environment can help strengthen the region's status
as an international financial, shipping, trade and tourism center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
