<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Telecom Group Obtains Huge Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South African
telecommunications group, Telkom announced today that it had
achieved excellent financial results for the year by the end of
March, with profit surging 61 percent from a 23 percent rise in
turnover.
</P>
<P>
Telkom said in a statement that its attributable profit has
improved to 1.95 billion Rand (433 million U.S. dollars) from
1.21 billion Rand (269 million U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Telkom earnings per share amounted to 50 cents, compared to 31
cents last year, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from calls within South Africa increased 24 percent to
12.05 billion Rand (2.68 billion U.S. dollars) while turnover
from international traffic grew by a moderate four percent to 2.8
billion Rand (622 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Given the good performance, said Telkom Chairman Dikgang
Moseneke, he was confident Telkom would meet the ambitious line
roll-out target set in its licence.
</P>
<P>
Telkom had targeted the roll-out of an additional 2.8 million
telephone lines before 2001, with a minimum of 256,000 lines
planned for underserviced areas in the coming fiscal year.
</P>
