<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong To Shake Off Poverty This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Economically-developed Guangdong
Province in south China has sent 130,000 officials to
disadvantaged areas to help the 600,000 poor people there shake
off poverty by the end of this year -- three years ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
The province has spent 230 million yuan on 220,000 poverty
relief projects since the beginning of the year. Each official
participating is charged with helping one of the 120,000 poor
families to get adequate food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
The most needy families were offered 1,000 yuan each to buy
chemical fertilizer, seeds and pesticides, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
And outside assistance for poverty relief is going strong, as
the eight coastal boomtowns, including Guangzhou, Shenzhen,
Zhuhai, and Shantou, are helping 16 poor counties, while 100 rich
townships in the Pearl River Delta area are doing the same for
another 100 townships in the northern mountain area.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has spent four billion yuan over the past 12 years on
aid-the-poor programs, building 1,800 agricultural production
bases and lifting 3.4 million people out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
China is fighting a nationwide anti-poverty campaign, in an
effort to help its remaining 58 million poor people have
sufficient food and clothing by the end of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
