<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: Globalization Brings Opportunities and Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- International Monetary Fund (IMF)
Managing Director Michel Camdessus said Wednesday that economic
globalization has opened new opportunities for investment and
growth in most developing countries, but also brought challenges
like marginalization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a high-level discussion on Wednesday organized by
the United Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC), Camdessus
said challenges remain for both developing countries and the less
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"For emerging market economies, one problem was how to maintain
market confidence and deal with the economic policy complications
that often accompany large capital inflows," he said.
</P>
<P>
"For less developed countries, often ignored by the markets, an
important question was how to deal with marginalization,"
Camdessus continued.
</P>
<P>
The IMF head said the IMF shared the ECOSOC's aim of fostering
an enabling environment for development in its mandate and
activities.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF's strategy started with helping countries
re-establish basic macroeconomic equilibrium and complete the
structural reforms needed to achieve a more efficient allocation
of resources and "jump-start" the engines of growth.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said an increasing number of countries had adopted
comprehensive programs of adjustment and reform in recent years,
many of them with IMF advice and support.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that a second generation of reforms was
necessary, including fiscal adjustment, bolder structural reforms,
better government and strengthened financial institutions, if
countries of all stages of development wanted to grasp the
opportunities of globalization and minimize the risks.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus told the meeting the IMF and the World Bank had
recently begun to implement a strategy to resolve the external
debt problems of heavily indebted, low-income countries, including
their large multilateral debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
