<HEADLINE> Albanian PM Urges Boosted Security for Run-offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino
on Wednesday ordered the police to strengthen public security in
order to make sure of a smooth second round of the parliamentary
election, scheduled on July 6.
</P>
<P>
Fino issued the decree immediately after President Sali
Berisha, who is also commander-in-chief of the country's armed
forces, ordered the republican guardsmen to undertake the
responsibility of maintaining public order.
</P>
<P>
Fino criticized Berisha's deployment, saying the republican
guardsmen's duty is to protect the president, the prime minister
and the speaker of parliament, instead of maintaining public
order, which is the duty of the police.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that Berisha is still commander-in-chief of
Albania's armed forces, but this does not mean he can break the
rules," Fino said.
</P>
<P>
The central electoral commission was still busily working on
the result of the first round of the election, but in a televised
speech on Monday, Berisha conceded the defeat of his party.
</P>
<P>
The commission said counting was complete in 72 of 115
constituencies run by majority voting but could not say how many
seats had been won by each party. Run-offs in districts where no
candidate reached 50 percent will be held next Sunday. 
</P>
