<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Normal yet Special Day for Banks in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Banks in this international
financial hub has had a normal but special business day today,
which is the first working day after Hong Kong's return to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
At 8:30 a.m., half an hour prior to the business hour,
Alexander S K Au, vice-chairman and chief executive of the Hang
Seng Bank, the second largest in Hong Kong, entered into his
office.
</P>
<P>
"During the morning meeting, the first thing I did was to brief
the senior executives on the speeches made by President Jiang
Zemin and Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa during the celebration
ceremony for the inauguration of the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)," Au told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Today is a very special day for Hong Kong since it marks a new
chapter for Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
"I'm very much encouraged by President Jiang's speech in which
he reiterated the "one country, two systems" concept, a "high
degree of autonomy", and "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong, as
well as by Tung Chee Hwa's remarks that all the successful
formulas of Hong Kong will remain unchanged."
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that Hong Kong people will be fully capable
of rising to the challenges and build a brighter future, and my
colleagues also share my feeling", he said.
</P>
<P>
In front of the Po Sang Bank, local residents, old and young,
were seen forming long queues in rain, awaiting to buy gold and
silver handover commemorative coins issued by the People's Bank of
China.
</P>
<P>
"At least they have to queue for a dozen hours before getting a
serial number for the purchase, and actually many of them have
been here for more than 20 hours," said Yen Sai Change, manager of
Business Promotion Department of the PO Sang Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the limited issue, gold coins are actually only
available to a few lucky ones and most of the people can only buy
one silver coin for each", Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
"It is worthwhile spending the time for the coin, since it is a
souvenir for the handover," said a young woman named Lee, who is
holding a baby in her arms.
</P>
<P>
Long queues also appeared in the business halls of major banks,
with all sorts of transaction, such as savings, lending, gold
trading and money changing being done in an orderly manner.
Friendly and polite service people are helping the clients in
Guangdong dialect, English and Putonghua (standard Chinese).
</P>
<P>
It is only normal for Hong Kongers to flock to banks after a
five-day holiday and in the beginning of a month, said Cecillia
Ko, a spokeswoman for the Hong Seng Bank and Dan Dan Chang,
External Relations manager of the Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank.
</P>
<P>
For Eddie T S Wang, assistant general manager and chief
executive officer China of the Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank,
described today as "an especially busy day".
</P>
<P>
"I've been kept receiving calls from clients who want to expand
 business in China, and this signals a good beginning," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, his bank's business momentum the interior
areas remains brisk.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which is the largest in Hong Kong, has already opened
seven branches, three representative offices and a sub-branch in
China.
</P>
<P>
"We're trying to upgrade our representative offices into
branches and busy training personnel for the expansion of China
business", he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
