<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Down Sharply during Handover Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- No crimes were reported in the
seven hours of celebrations of Hong Kong's return to China on July
1, according to the Hong Kong police.
</P>
<P>
A senior police officer said that police sent out nearly 5,000
police officers to maintain order during Hong Kong '97
Spectacular, a celebration event that drew 800,000 residents in
Tsim Sha Tsui in Kowloon alone, 500,000 more than the historical
record.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of crimes over the past three days was also
sharply lower than in normal times, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure security during the handover ceremonies, the police
started to make preparations more than a year ago, and purchased
and leased a large amount of advanced security equipment, he
added.
</P>
<P>
From June 30 to July 2, more than two thirds of the Hong Kong
police were mobilized for security during handover ceremony and
celebrations, 2,200 police officers were dispatched to the Hong
Kong Convention and Exhibition Center alone, the venue for the
handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The officer said that during the five-day public holiday for
the handover from June 28 to July 2, Hong Kong was constantly
drenched in torrential rains, which resulted in severe traffic
jams and caused bigger difficulties for the police to carry out
its duty.
</P>
<P>
But all police officers are in high spirits because everyone
wants to contribute to maintaining Hong Kong's stability, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
