<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
retreated from an all-time intraday high to close slightly lower
today, with key resource stocks falling but retail and building
companies gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed three points softer
at 2742.9, off a record intraday high of 2757.9 in morning trade.
</P>
<P>
"It was a quieter day and there's not as much impetus in the
market today as there has been recently," Shaw Stockbroking's
Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
"There was some profit-taking in some stocks which have been
very keenly sought after, some of the leading banks came (down),
and gold's very weak with the lower bullion price overnight."
</P>
<P>
A broker said the domestic market would consolidate at these
levels until there was some more economic news from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 9.1 points to 4338.9 while the
all resources index lost 14.3 points to 1508.8.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, ANZ slid 16 cents to 9.75 Australian dollars,
National Australia Bank went down four cents at 19.35 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth gained one cent to 16.02 Australian dollars
and Westpac lost three cents to 7.94 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Macquaire Bank jumped 25 cents to 11.80 Australian dollars. It
was named as part of the syndicate for construction of Sydney's
new underground eastern suburb railway.
</P>
<P>
Among resource companies, diversified miner Rio Tinto fell 57
cents to 22.40 Australian dollars, BHP slipped 15 to 19.68
Australian dollars and Comalco shed 10 to 7.05 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slid 37.5 points to 1428.1 while in Sydney gold
bullion was trading at 332.00 US dollars per fine ounce -- down
from yesterday's close of 332.35 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 354.18 million shares worth 953.51
million Australian dollars (715.13 million US dollars) with rises
outnumbering falls 564 to 546.  
</P>
</TEXT>
