<HEADLINE> PLA Hong Kong Troops' Fine Image Admired  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stonecutters Island Naval Base -- Cheng Feng, a PLA Company
commander assigned tasks to soldiers coming off sentry this
morning when a mini bus with three passengers was driving past the
entrance of the barracks.
</P>
<P>
Noticing the road is wet and narrow, Cheng and two of his men
moved a number of steps away and made way especially for the mini
bus to pass by, but their shoes became saturated with rainwater.
</P>
<P>
This apparently moved a passenger, who thumbed up and expressed
his thanks in his imperfect Putonghua, or standard Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a taxi driver named Cai, came across this scene and
said, "I was really excited when I saw PLA soldiers move into this
former barracks of British troops for more than 100 years. Now
I've witnessed with my own eyes how polite and humane these PLA
soldiers are," he said.
</P>
<P>
When reporters mounted aboard the "Shunde" missile corvette, Ji
Zhong, a soldier, stood guard on the deck. Though he did not get
any sleep on July 1, he was joyous and in high spirit.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, right after the first navy vessel reached
the base at 7:24 a.m., the sailors aboard the two vessels were
immediately told to perform duty. Up to now, not a single soldier
left his post.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Liqing, a nurse and the only seawoman of the PLA Hong Kong
Garrison navy, noted that all the sailors and officers have been
in a very good condition, since the navy vessel moved from the
base in Shantou of Guangdong Province to Hong Kong,
</P>
<P>
Moreover, according to Huang Chuangou, a lieutenant commander,
the officers and sailors are fully capable of adapting themselves
to adverse weather conditions and perform their duties well.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Barracks, -- everything is kept spick-and-span and
arranged in order at the barracks for the PLA ground force at
Stanley, Gallipoli Lines, Gun Club Hill and Osborn barracks.
</P>
<P>
The afternoon of July 2 was set aside to study laws for the
troops stationed at Shek Kong Camp. The half day was spent to read
a series of books concerning the Basic Law and other laws of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to an officer, although all the men have passed law
examinations, their enthusiasm for learning the law related
knowledge remains.
</P>
<P>
"The troops' sense of responsibility is acute and strong. They
reached consensus that only with the best command of the law
related knowledge can they guarantee the high-standard
accomplishment of the duty", the officer said.
</P>
<P>
Every morning, the officers and soldiers of a company named
after the Dadu river heroic operation during the world-renowned
Long March of 1934-35 cleaned all roads in their barracks and
sentry guards performed routine checks on vehicles entering
barracks area with politeness, and their serious yet polite manner
won the trust of local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Work Day of HKSAR Justice Department </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- "I am so excited," Elsie Leung
Oi-sie, Secretary of Justice of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), told a roomful of journalists in
her office with a smile.
</P>
<P>
Leung, one of the three leading departmental secretaries of the
HKSAR government, arrived at her office in the Queensway
Government Offices building at 8 a.m. today, the first working day
after the establishment of HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have much time for you, because I have to visit all
the offices to meet every staff member of my department," Leung,
in a dark elegant suit, apologized to the reporters, who were busy
at shooting pictures.
</P>
<P>
Leung, a barrister, is the first Chinese as well as the first
female in the Hong Kong history to serve as head of the Department
of Justice, which is charge of providing legal advice for the
administration, drafting legal documents, lodging criminal
prosecutions and handling other legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 Chinese and foreign journalists came to the
Department of Justice to cover its first working day. In order not
to disturb the work of the department, TV reporters had to wait
outside in the lift lobby, while print reporters were admitted
first.
</P>
<P>
S. Hoosain, chief information officer of the Secretary of
Justice's Office, gave his name cards to the reporters when they
entered the office area.
</P>
<P>
While one reporter said that he had already got his card
previously, Hoosain said seriously: "These are new ones -- I'm now
working with the HKSAR Department of Justice."
</P>
<P>
In every office with its door open, staff members were busy
working and didn't take a glance at the passing-by journalists.
</P>
<P>
"The nearly 1,000 staff members of our department all came to
work in time this morning," Hoosain said, "They are now busy
handling business piled up over the past five public holidays."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Law Officer Bob Allcock, who is a foreign national, told
the reporters that the legal system of the HKSAR would not
experience great changes in accordance with the Basic Law, and
that the Department of Justice would continue to serve the
community.
</P>
<P>
Allcock, who said he had cooperated with his new boss Elsie
Leung before in preparing the Reunification Bill, added that the
maintenance of Hong Kong's current bi-lingual legal system has
enabled non-Chinese-speaking foreign lawyers like him to continue
to work without difficulty.
</P>
<P>
"For us, life and work will go on as usual," he said. "I will
continue working here as long as possible."
</P>
<P>
Information officer Hoosain said that a quarter of the nearly
300 government lawyers of the Department of Justice are foreign
nationals. Two of the five of Law Officers, who are next to the
Secretary of Justice in position, are foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
"All of them have retained their posts and will continue to
serve the SAR," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
