<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Smuggling Egyptian Antiquities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Embassy here has denied any
involvement in the largest ever antiquities smuggling in Egypt,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Neither U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Edward Walker nor any of his
predecessors have ever been involved in such operations," an
embassy source was quoted as saying. "This applies to all of the
present and former employees of the U.S. Embassy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian police have foiled an attempt to smuggle to
Switzerland a cache of 3,000-year-old antiquities which include
the head of a statue of Pharaoh Ahmose, the founder of the 18th
dynasty, and a rare collection of glassware.
</P>
<P>
The smugglers had tried to disguise the 210-kilogram
antiquities shipment as the personal belongings of the incumbent
U.S. Ambassador before it was intercepted by the Antiquities
Police and the Cairo Airport Police.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Interior Minister for Tourism and Antiquities Police
Mohammed el-Sham told a press conference Tuesday that
investigations showed that the smuggling gang including a custom
official forged letters from the U.S. Embassy and the Egyptian
Foreign Ministry and mentioned the name of Edward Walker in them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ali Hassan, the secretary-general of the Supreme
Council for Antiquities, told the press conference that the
recovered items will be put on display at the Egyptian Museum here.
</P>
<P>
Egypt bans the export of all antiquities but smuggling is
rampant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
