<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Fails to Move on Rates, Australian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Australia's
(RBA's) failure to cut interest rates this morning spurred the
Australian dollar to a new high, but couldn't lift it above its
previous finish against its US counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended in Sydney at 75.30 US cents, down
from yesterday's close of 75.48 US cents, but higher than its
opening level of 75.19. Overnight, it was traded as high as 78.56
US cents in London.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank's manager of foreign exchange trading Stuart
Moore said the local currency moved up to between 75.30 US cents
and 75.40 US cents this morning after the RBA, the central bank,
was silent on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The bank held its monthly board meeting on Tuesday and the
market has since been keeping an eye out for a possible
announcement on easing official cash rate. The bank eased rates to
5.5 percent on May 23 bringing in line with the US official rate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Commonwealth Bank economist Michael Blythe said in a
statement that assuming the Australian dollar can successfully
navigate the next few weeks, interest rate fears are expected to
be appeased by the stronger activity that forward indicators
suggest is on the way.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was 86.13 yen from 86.47 yesterday, and
at 1.3102 marks from 1.3170.  
</P>
</TEXT>
