<HEADLINE> Arafat Wraps up Two-day Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt pledged to continue its
mediation efforts to revive the deadlocked Mideast peace process
as Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
wrapped up a two-day visit here today.
</P>
<P>
Arafat left here for Gaza after talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak at the presidential palace this morning, but he made
no remarks at the end of the 75-minute meeting.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
told reporters that the summit talks focused on the worsening
conditions in occupied lands and the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that Egypt's contacts with Israel and the PNA will
continue, but stressed that the two sides have to exert more
efforts to move forward the peace march.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts will go on but the basis for their continuation
would depend on the outcome of the Palestinian-Israeli contacts,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that contacts between the Palestinians and Israelis
will continue over some of the issues raised for discussion at the
negotiating table such as "confidence-building steps, settlements
and others."
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for the results of these contacts," he said,
pointing out that conditions at present are "still the same."
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he cannot predict at the moment if there will be "a
progress, an improvement or any new development."
</P>
<P>
International mediating efforts have failed to bring the two
sides back to the negotiating table three months after the Israeli
peace talks collapsed when Israel began building a new
neighborhood for Jews.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Israeli troops shot dead a Palestinian teenager
in clashes over a disputed strip of land in the PNA-ruled Gaza,
while 37 Arabs were wounded during a protest against anti-Muslim
posters.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said Tuesday that Egypt would not for
the time being resume its negotiating efforts but contacts between
the two sides would materialize in progress soon.
</P>
<P>
"Let them work: I hope they can conclude something within one
week, 10 days," he told reporters during an inspection tour to the
western desert in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Arafat flew here Wednesday night at the end of his brief
visits to France, Tunisia and Algeria, where he held talks on the
staggering Palestinian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit was aimed at briefing Mubarak on the details of
the present crisis facing the peace march in the region and
ongoing endeavors to get out of this crisis, PNA Minister of
Planning and International Cooperation Nabiel Shaath said in
statements today.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of holding a tri-partite summit
among Mubarak, Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu within one week.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stepped in as the main mediator between the
Palestinians and Israelis over the past few weeks as a result of
what many Arabs perceive as a lack of U.S. interest in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has sent his senior advisor Osama el-Baz to shuttle
between the two sides several times in a bid to revive the peace
talks but the gap remains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
