<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges Warring Afghan Factions to Take </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today urged the Afghan
Taliban militia and the opposition northern alliance to take some
confidence-building measures to remove the mistrust existing
between them.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides are far apart, our effort is to try to narrow
their differences," said Iftikhar Murshed, Additional Secretary of
the Foreign Ministry, when briefing newsmen about his shuttle
diplomacy on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Murshed said he launched his shuttle diplomacy at the behest of
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif who wanted Afghan groups to sit across
a negotiating table to hammer out their differences.
</P>
<P>
"There is a great mistrust between them and there is a need for
taking confidence-building measures to bridge that gap," he said.
</P>
<P>
Giving details of his meetings with Afghan leaders, Murshed
said he met with a delegation of the north-based Afghan opposition
led by Younas Qanooni in Dubai on June 18.
</P>
<P>
He said the opposition delegation, which included
representatives from the ousted Afghan government of Professor
Burhanuddin Rabbani, Hezb-e-Wehdat of Karim Khalili and
Jumbish-e-Milli of General Malik, proposed the formation of a
political commission to ponder over the establishment of a
broad-based government in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, he said, also proposed that the political
commission should meet in Kabul, for which the capital should be
demilitarized.
</P>
<P>
Murshed said he visited the Taliban leadership in Kandahar on
June 26 to convey the proposals of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's "Foreign Minister" Mulla Jalil and Acting
"President" Mulla Rabbani favored a peaceful political settlement
of the Afghan conflict, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the Taliban suggested that formation of any
political commission should be preceded by a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"How do you expect us to talk when rockets are falling around
us," he quoted Taliban officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban leaders also called for the release of
their prisoners including former "Foreign Minister" Mulla Ghous
and State Bank governor Mullah Ehsanullah.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani diplomat said the Afghan opposition confirmed
that the arrested Taliban officials are alive, and they promised
"to get back to us in a couple of days about their release."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the possibility of a ceasefire, Murshed said,
"I have got the impression they are agreeable to ceasefire."
</P>
<P>
"Each side says it will stop fighting if the other does so," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
