<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Museum Gets Face-Lifting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Some of the world's most fascinating
antiquities are seeing the light of the day for the first time as
the Egyptian Museum began interior improvements to make itself a
better place for visitors.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made this summer to develop the Egyptian
Museum's second floor, where the treasures connected to the
family of Akhenaten (1370-1352 BC), the pharaoh famed for his
monotheistic beliefs are stored, Egyptian Al Ahram Weekly
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mask of Yuya, Akhenaten's grandfather, has been restored
from the basement and put on permanent display for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The cartonnage-made mask, painted in gold and decorated with
semi-precious stones and colored glass, is one of the most
intriguing exhibits in the museum.
</P>
<P>
Another improvement in the museum is the renovation of two
jewelery rooms, where royal treasures from the three "great"
periods of Ancient Egyptian history, the Old, Middle and New
Kingdoms, are displayed.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to provide a new layout and decoration for
both chambers, as well as to install new lighting, ventilation
and air-conditioning systems, and specially designed showcases.
</P>
<P>
The project, carried out at the cost of 180,000 Egyptian
pounds (more than 52,900 U.S. dollars), is being financed by the
museum's budget, together with the donations of Egyptian
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Museum is currently preparing for a major
overhaul of collection of Pharaoh Tutankhamun (who was during the
reign of 1361 BC to 1352 BC) in order to upgrade the displays
before next November's celebration of the 75th anniversary of the
discovery of the tomb by the British archaeologist, Howard Carter.
</P>
<P>
Experts in art, education and museum design from the Dutch
Cultural Foundation, and the American Research Center in Egypt
will collaborate to implement the project, scheduled to be
completed by November.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Museum houses a collection of paintings and
sculptures on the history of Egypt from the prehistoric periods,
ancient Egyptian, Greco-Roman, Coptic and Islamic to the
present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
