<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hollywood Bowl Hosts '97 Bravo China Spectacular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 2 (Xinhua) -- One of the largest natural
amphitheaters in the world, the Hollywood Bowl here, for the first
time received a group of Chinese artists, on a special occasion.
</P>
<P>
This evening, two days after the return of Hong Kong to China,
the world-famous Hollywood Bowl hosted 1997 Bravo China music and
dance with fireworks spectacular. With a seating capacity of
20,000, the amphitheater was packed with native Californians and
those of Chinese origin.
</P>
<P>
Two American young men, carrying a banner bearing the words
"Congratulating Hong Kong's Return to China," greeted the audience
at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
It was indeed a night of China, Chinese music and dance as well
as Chinese art and culture. It also was a night of Chinese and
Western cultural exchange.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 colorful silk lanterns hung on both sides of the
theater. Conspicuous in front of the gate was a huge float
decorated with a dragon and phoenix, 15 meters long and 7 meters
wide, symbolizing the Chinese theme.
</P>
<P>
With the collaboration of the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra,
world-acclaimed Chinese singers, musicians and dancers presented
solos, duet, Chinese folk dance "Peacock," pas de deux, and
concertos for cello, piano and violin.
</P>
<P>
A good combination of Chinese and Western music was
demonstrated by an erhu (a two-string Chinese instrument) concerto
of the Hungarian csardas, and violin concerto of the Chinese
romance Butterfly Lovers. Highlighting erhu and other Chinese
instruments, the orchestra also performed suite on themes of
Chinese folk music.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the area's magnificent climate, concerts are held at
the 75-year-old Bowl almost every evening throughout the summer,
together with fireworks.
</P>
<P>
Tonight's traditional fireworks also had a Chinese meaning in
it: emerging from the smoke were the patterns of dragon and
phoenix, both Chinese mascots, as well as a bell tower and
pagoda. When the words "Bravo China" finally appeared on top of
the stage, the concert came to an end amid applause and music.
</P>
<P>
On the second floor of the theater, folk artists from China's
Shanghai gave a live performance of papercut, embroidery and
carving. Paintings by overseas Chinese artists also were
exhibited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Situation in Malaysia Worrying: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS situation in Malaysia
is worrying, Malaysian AIDS Council President Marina Mahathir said
today.
</P>
<P>
The increasing number of AIDS cases being detected is likely to
diminish the country's younger generation unless anti-AIDS
measures are effectively enforced, Marina said when launching an
AIDS Awareness Week organized by Malaya University.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21,026 HIV carriers and AIDS cases had been detected
since 1993 till last March, Marina said.
</P>
<P>
"These are reported cases, but there are probably many more
unreported," she said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting reports, Marina said some 300 AIDS and HIV cases were
detected each month, and the number rose to 380 last month.
</P>
<P>
Those within the 18 and 39 years age group accounted for the
largest number of the patients, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Council has devised various programs in its
fight against the killer disease, including a study on its effects
on the national economy and social life.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
