<HEADLINE> Namibia Breweries Raps S. African for Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Namibia Breweries (Nambrew)
has accused South African Breweries (SAB) of dumping inferior
products on the Namibian market, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a media briefing on Wednesday in Windhoek, capital
of Namibia, Nambrew Managing Director Bernd Masche said the
accusation was referring to the SAB's recent introduction of a
non-returnable 750ml bottle into the Namibian market.
</P>
<P>
Mashce said the SAB bottles could be confused with Nambrew's
750ml returnable bottles, adding SAB's bottle were also made of
thinner glass, which could result in the bottles exploding.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nambrew Marketing Director Ernst Ender said the
SAB's new bottles added a pollution factor, which he said was
highly irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to promote the returnable bottle concept in
Namibia, but now SAB has brought in a pollution factor. Their
adverts also don't say that the bottles are non-returnable," said
Ender.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports published on the Namibian newspapers
today, the new SAB bottles, which were only marketed in Namibia
and not in South Africa, would cause confusion in the local
market and lead to financial losses for Nambrew. 
</P>
</TEXT>
