<HEADLINE> New Territorial Dispute Between Nigeria, Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A new territorial dispute has
emerged between Nigeria and Cameroun which have already engaged
in hostilities over the territorial sovereignty in the oil-rich
Bakassi Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria today, Cameroun is
claiming the territorial sovereignty over the fertile Darak
Island in the northeastern state of Borno near Lake Chad.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has taken steps to defend the new case
of border dispute instituted against it by Cameroun at the
International Court of Justice, the official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
A team of legal experts defending Nigeria in the case has
already visited Borno for a physical inspection of the disputed
island, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Darak case is the second instituted against Nigeria by
Cameroun after that of Bakassi Peninsula in the southeastern
border. Both countries have troops stationed in the peninsula, an
oil-rich territory of about 1,000 square km in the Gulf of
Guinea. Repeated clashes have been reported between the two
countries in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The Bakassi case is pending the judgement of the world court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
