<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Form New Ties with Russia: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming visit of
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan to Russia is "part of
our efforts to forge new linkages with Russia," a Foreign Office
spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question about Gohar's visit to Russia, the
spokesman told a weekly news conference that it would be a two-day
working visit, which will take place on July 8-9.
</P>
<P>
"We considered Russia as an important neighbor of us and we
consider Russia a country who can play a very useful role in
maintenance of peace and stability in this region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We feel that it is important for our government that came to
power a few months ago to establish an understanding with the
leadership in Russia as well," he added.
</P>
<P>
To another question, he said a Russian deputy foreign minister
during his recent visit to Pakistan gave a positive response to
Pakistan's proposal for holding a conference involving the
region's countries on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Afghanistan will figure in the foreign
minister's visit in Moscow," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also confirmed that Pakistan had carried out a
test of the Hataf missile, saying "it was a routine test and had
no military component."
</P>
<P>
The test was carried out by SUPARCO, a civilian organization,
whose activities were geared towards the civilian sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on a report that Pakistan test-fired the
Hataf-III missile, the spokesman said that the SUPARCO is engaged
in a peaceful research for the development of rocket motor
technology.
</P>
<P>
The organization carried out the routine test of rockets from
time to time and "these rockets are aimed at peaceful uses of this
particular technology", he said.  
</P>
