<HEADLINE> Manila Turns Down Proposed Mediation in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A top Philippine government peace
negotiator today turned down a proposal by the rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) for an independent foreign group to
mediate in the stalled peace talks between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
"I do not approve of such proposal," Fortunato Abat, chairman
of the government peace negotiating panel, told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need for that," said Abat, adding that the MILF
should return to the negotiating table and talk peace with the
government "if they want peace."
</P>
<P>
Ghazali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, had
proposed that a foreign third party mediate in the peace talks
between the government and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF panel has also asked that the peace talks be
postponed indefinitely, in view of the recent bloody clashes
between government troops and MILF forces in central Mindanao, the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The battles between the military and the MILF broke out when
the MILF took hostage some 100 passengers of two buses and one
trailer along a main highway in Central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The fierce fighting also killed more than 100 rebels, soldiers
and civilians, forcing some 65,000 civilians to flee their homes
at the height of clashes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
