<HEADLINE> Mubarak Receives Message From Saudi Monarch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today received a message from King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz of Saudi
Arabia on coordinating Arab stance, the Egyptian MENA news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The message was handed over by Saudi Foreign Minister Saud
al-Faisal Al-Saud during his meeting with the president this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting, Faisal told reporters that the
message came within the context of sustained consultations and
coordination between the two countries regarding challenges facing
the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi top diplomat played down the possibility of holding
an Arab summit in the face of the present deadlock in the Mideast
peace march, saying that the resolutions approved by the last
pan-Arab summit held here a year ago reflected a clear-cut Arab
stance on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Faisal made it clear that it is the Israeli policy, instead of
the Arab stance, that poses a major threat to the peace march and
poisons the necessary atmospheres for the peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
"Saudi Arabia does not seek adopting a certain stance regarding
any topic but rather it is the Israeli policy which poses a
threat," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi foreign minister, who arrived here Wednesday night,
also met with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa. Later today,
they will co-chair the meetings of the Egyptian-Saudi Higher Joint
Committee, which are aimed at discussing cooperation between the
two countries in all fields.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is Egypt's largest trade partner in the Arab
world, with the volume of trade exchange totaling 2 billion
Egyptian pounds (588 million U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are also discussing the possibility of
setting up a trade free zone on the coast of Red Sea that will open
to all Arab investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
