<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Cautions on ECOMOG Strike against Koroma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A Liberian diplomat here has called
for caution in the proposed use of force by the west African
peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) to oust coupists in Sierra Leone to
avoid spill-over to neighboring countries, local newspaper
Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG should assess its ability to carry out a "surgical
military operation" in Sierra Leone and take out its target
within a short period, said Sabato Wiah, press and cultural
counsellor of the Liberian Embassy to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) leaders to do their best to prevent a spill-over of the
crisis in Sierra Leone to Liberia, saying that the proliferation
of arms in that country could cause instability in Liberia
because the two countries share a common border.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, with more than 11,000 troops operating in Liberia for
about seven years, has tightened security corridors in the
country and put in place its security dragnet to prevent any
group from using the country's territory as a launching base.
</P>
<P>
However, Wiah said the porousity of most African borders,
including Liberia, should be of concern, adding that he preferred
the resolution of Sierra Leone's crisis in a manner that would
not create refugee problem in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS is in talks with Sierra Leone's military junta led by
Major Johnny Paul Koroma, which seized power in a coup on May 25.
According to a decision reached at an ECOWAS foreign ministers
meeting on June 26, an embargo and use of force will be
implemented to oust the junta if peaceful settlement cannot be
achieved during two weeks' talks.
</P>
<P>
Only two days ago, ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor
Malu said the sub-regional force was capable of flushing out the
coupists in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
