<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Food Export to be Curbed in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The government of Tanzania
is planning to impose stern measures against people involved in
illegally exporting food crops, especially maize and beans, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State in the Prime Minister's Office Kingunge N.
Mwiru told journalists in Dodoma, central Tanzania on Wednesday
that the food situation in the country is at an alarming
situation and all necessary efforts should be made to preserve
food crops.
</P>
<P>
He said around 500,000 tons of grain will be needed to
supplement what will be harvested in various regions. "We have
started buying maize from farmers, and we also welcome business
people to do the same in the efforts to save the nation from
famine," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mwiru said 80 percent of peasants in Dodoma Region will not
harvest because there was insufficient rains. "I visited the
region last weekend," said the minister, adding, "there was no
hope to harvest enough food crops."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that five billion Tanzania Shillings has
already been set aside by the government to purchase maize and
beans.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Canada, Australia, Ireland, Germany, and
Belgium through the World Food Program (WFP) have promised about
3.59 million U.S. Dollars to support Tanzanian government's
efforts to save the nation from famine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
