<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Chief Calls for Help For Least-Developed Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- World Trade Organization (WTO)
Director-General Renato Ruggiero has called on major international
organizations to make further efforts to help least-developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a high-level discussion on Wednesday organized by
the United Nations Economic and Social Council, Ruggiero said that
more needed to be done to help least-developed countries foster an
enabling environment for development in the course of world
economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral trading system was itself a key element in
fostering an enabling environment for development, Ruggiero told
the meeting. It helped all countries relate to the basic fact of
globalization within a framework which opened opportunities and
provided the security of agreed rights and obligations.
</P>
<P>
"To fully reflect the interests and objectives of
least-developed countries, these countries have to be able to use
it (the multilateral trading system) fully," Ruggiero said.
</P>
<P>
"A key contribution of the WTO, working closely with the UNCTAD
(the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development) and the
International Trade Center, is technical assistance for building
trade policy expertise in these countries. We are also employing
new technologies much more extensively to extend the reach and the
effectiveness of that assistance, and to make technical
information more relevant to specific economic needs," he added.
</P>
<P>
The WTO, with the UNCTAD, the International Trade Center and
other major multilateral institutions, will organize a high-level
meeting for least-developed countries to forge an integrated
response to the challenges facing such countries, Ruggiero said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
