<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sets New Date for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's presidential and
governorship elections have been rescheduled to come up on the
same day -- August 1, 1998, according to an adjusted transition
to civil rule timetable released on Wednesday in capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Two months later, the president will be sworn in and the
National Assembly inaugurated on October 1.
</P>
<P>
In the revised timetable, the National Assembly election has
been fixed for April 25, 1998, while the State Assembly elections
will take place on December 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
Party primaries at state and national levels for the
nomination of governorship and presidential candidates are to be
held between June 8 and 20, next year.
</P>
<P>
According to the military administration's three-year
transition to civil rule program announced in October 1995,
governorship elections would take place in the fourth quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The five political parties registered in October last year,
together with the Transition Implementation Committee and the
National Electoral Commission of Nigeria, asked earlier this year
for a shift of governorship elections as it would be undemocratic
to have elected governors at the state level and the military at
the center.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Ruling Council, the highest decision-making
body of the country, gave its final approval to the proposal last
week.
</P>
<P>
The latest amendment is one of a series of changes to the
transition program. And the flexibility of the timetable has
aroused concern both at home and abroad over the genuine
intention of the military administration.
</P>
<P>
Although official explanation of the amendment is yet to come,
the authorities have repeatedly vowed the hand-over date of
October 1, 1998 will not change even if other things changed.
</P>
<P>
With many of the key items on the revised timetable having
specific time pegs on them, what is urgently needed is the
government's activities to keep faith with the present schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Russia Discuss Nuclear Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Russia are holding talks
here to discuss an agreement on bilateral nuclear cooperation,
according to a local press report today.
</P>
<P>
The official English daily Tehran Times reported that the
agreement aims at exercising control and supervision of the
design and execution of the Bushehr atomic power plant.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the first round of the talks between the
two sides was held on Wednesday following the Russian delegation's
arrival Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not mention who heads the Russian
delegation. It said that the head of the Supreme Government
Atomic Supervision Organization of the Russian Federation arrived
in Tehran at the invitation of the Iran Atomic Energy
Organization.
</P>
<P>
On January 8, Iran and Russia signed the nuclear power
contract to complete a 1,000 megawatt power nuclear plant left
unfinished by a German company.
</P>
<P>
The 1 billion U.S.-dollar contract was signed here by Russian
Atomic Energy Minister Viktor Mikhailov and Reza Amrollahi,
Iranian Vice-President and head of Atomic Energy Organization of
Iran (AEOI).
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, Russia will help Iran complete the Bushehr
nuclear power plant in southern Iran by supplying equipment and
facilities as well as raw materials such as fuel for operation.
</P>
<P>
Russian Minister of Atomic Energy Viktor Mikhailov said on
June 24 this year that Russian contractors are proceeding with
a nuclear power plant commissioned by Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that the plant which is under construction in Bushehr
would be delivered to Iran on schedule. Russian contractors have
no problem with the building of the plant and the project is also
under the surveillance of the International Atomic Energy
Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
