<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- One day after the death of Hollywood star Robert Mitchum,
another legend of American movie, James Stewart, died on Wednesday
in Beverly Hills at 89. Stewart symbolized the idealism of the
Roosevelt era, and incarnated the detached heros of such great
movies as ``Life Is Beautiful,'' ``Vertigo'' and ``Window
Overlooking the Courtyard.''
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
Wednesday reached a compromise on whether France should continue the
process of fully returning to the integrated military structure of
NATO. They agreed that Paris will continue negotiations with the
United States on building a greater ``visibility'' of Europe in the
European part of NATO after the Madrid summit of the trans-Atlantic
alliance is held on July 8-9.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin is more and more inclined to
raise taxes upon French enterprises in order to balance the budget.
The government spokeswoman Catherine Trautmann said on Wednesday
that the government could ``require the effort of enterprises which
have made profits'' to improve the situation of public financial
situation. The Paris Bourse reacted negatively to the news with its
CAC 40 index dropping by 1.17 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- Some 1,000 tons of British beef have been illegally exported
via Northern Ireland to Europe, especially France, Spain and the
Netherlands, since the European Union imposed an embargo on British
beef export because of the mad cow disease in March 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
