<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Planes Attack Guerrilla South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes carried out this
morning an air raid at suspected targets of Lebanese resistance
guerrillas in the Saida area in the western part of south Lebanon
without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that the Israeli warplanes launched the
air raid at 5:40 a.m. local time (02:40 GMT) and fired two
air-to-surface missiles at the vicinities of Kfar Melki, 59
kilometers south of the Lebanese capital of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The air raid was the last of a series of exchange of fire
between Hezbollah guerrillas on the one side and the Israeli
forces and their client militia of the South Lebanon Army (SLA) on
the other since this week.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian Shiite Hezbollah, or Party of God, announced
that its guerrillas fired a volley of Katyusha rockets at the
Israeli position of Demashigiyeh in Jezzine in the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone" over the night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Radio claimed that the Galilee panhandle in northern
Israel was hit by mortar shells this morning.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Israeli warplanes launched an air raid on
Wednesday night at guerrilla targets in the eastern sector of
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
General Amiran Livine, chief of Israel's Northern Command,
confirmed that dozens of mortar shells and probably Katyusha
rockets, were fired into the buffer zone in south Lebanon and
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
He warned of an escalated violence against south Lebanese
villages, threatening that the Israeli forces would not stand
with bound hand and foot if the guerrillas continued opening fire
from these villages.
</P>
<P>
Amid the escalating tensions, Lebanese guerrillas waged a
bombing attack on a convoy of the Israeli-backed SLA militia on
Wednesday night in Jezzine, where one SLA officer was killed and
three other militiamen were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The Israel radio also said that one guerrilla was killed and
several others wounded in a clash with the Israeli occupation
forces on Wednesday night near Maidoum, Western Beqqa.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance, the military wing of Hezbollah,
announced that its fighters foiled an infiltrating attempt by
Israeli commandos in the Nabatiyeh area in western sector in the
south.
</P>
<P>
A civilian was injured Wednesday when dozens of shells
slammed into villages southeast of Nabatiyeh in retaliation of an
earlier resistance attack on an Israeli motorized patrol.
</P>
<P>
Five houses and five cars in Kfar Tibnit were also damaged as
Israeli gunners fired around 70 shells at the village and the
nearby areas of Arnoun and Yohmor, a Lebanese police spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientist Invents New Method to Diagnose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli scientist has
invented a new method to distinguish between malignant and benign
tumors that may also help establish the prognosis of cancer and
monitor therapy's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
The non-invasive method was developed by Professor Hadassa
Degani from the Weizman Institute, the July issue of the Nature
Medicine magzine published today reported in its cover story.
</P>
<P>
The method consists of injecting a contrast-enhancing dye-like
material into the patient's bloodstream and using magnetic
resonance imaging (MRI) to follow the way this material is
absorbed and evacuated by the tumor. Because the uptake and
clearance differ in cancerous and benign tumors, such monitoring
makes a diagnosis possible.
</P>
<P>
A computer shows an image on a screen in various colors,
reflecting the distribution of the contrast material. The color
patterns for malignant and benign growths are strikingly
different, Degani said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the method thus could reduce the number of
biopsis performed to diagnose tumors. "Most breast tumors
detected by mammography prove to be benign in a biopsy, so that a
non-invasive method like MRI could help reduce the rate of
unnecessary procedures," Degani said.
</P>
<P>
The method could also tell doctors the prognosis of cancer
because it reveals tiny blood vessels that feed the cancer (in a
process called angiogenesis) and allow the tumor to grow and
spread. Knowing their density and ability to deliver materials to
the tumor may make it possible to determine the tumor's potential
aggressiveness, said Degani.
</P>
<P>
Monitoring the blood vessels and the spaces between cells may
also help evaluate the efficiency of treatment. A reduction in the
vessel's density and an increase in intra-cellular spaces could
point to successful therapy, She added.
</P>
<P>
In conventional MRI, signals emanating from the nuclei of
hydrogen atoms that make up water in the tissues are too weak to
produce a resolution comparable to that under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
But in Degani's method, resolution is very high because the
water-tissue signals are recorded over an extended period - two
to four minutes instead of the usual several seconds, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Goes Ahead With Regional Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 3 (Xinhua)-- Qatar will go ahead with
preparations to host the fourth Middle East and North Africa
Economic conference in November despite of pressure from other
Arab countries to cancel or postpone it, a local newspaper said
today.
</P>
<P>
"Our main task at present is to make arrangements for the
conference and we are going ahead with it," Gulf News quoted
Qatar's Minister of State For Foreign Affairs Ahmed bin Abdullah
al Mahmoud as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Qatar minister made the remarks Wednesday after signing a
contract with Qatar Airways appointing it as "official carrier"
for the conference.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who attended the Damascus Declaration meeting in
Syria last month, denied reports that the foreign ministers at the
meeting had opposed the holding of the conference due to take
place in the Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
"I personally attended that meeting and was happy at the
proceedings. The ministers did not take any such decision," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Syria and some of other Arab countries have tried to mobilize
oppositon to the conference where Israel's participation is
expected, to protest against Israel's hardline policy in the
stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Syria boycotted the previous three because of Israel's
participation. It said that Israel should not obtain economic
rewards from such meetings.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud said that it was not decided whether Israel will be
invited to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
"As of now, we are only occupied with making
arrangements...invitations will go out only a few weeks before
the conference date," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has expected between 2,500 to 3,000 delegates from the
world including Israel to conference, saying the meeting is just
an economic forum.
</P>
<P>
"It is a purely economic forum and we expected Israel to
participate in it," a senior official in Qatar's Ministry of
Foreign Affairs said in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
