<HEADLINE> 3,000 Philippine Evacuees Infected by Minor Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 evacuees in the
southern Philippines have been infected by various minor diseases,
a provincial health official said today.
</P>
<P>
Maguindanao province health chief Tahir Sulaik said that cases
like coughs, flu, headache, fever, ulcers, skin diseases,
gastroenteritis, hypertension and pneumonia have been reported in
some evacuation centers.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency quoted Sulaik as saying that so far,
there were no reported outbreak of diseases in any of the
evacuation centers in the province.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department estimated there are about 65,500 evacuees
in several evacuation centers after two week fierce conflicts
between government troops and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) rebels in Maguindanao and North Cotabato province.
</P>
<P>
Sulaik assured that all of the reported disease cases have
already been attended to by health workers and the Health
Department has taken all possible measures to prevent outbreaks of
diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
