<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Set to Meet Growth Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
is set to meet its ambitious growth targets and achieve the
reduction of the budget deficit to four percent of gross domestic
product (GDP) this year, a local daily Sowetan reported today.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel said on Wednesday that higher
export figures of 2.74 billion U.S. Dollars in May, and an
apparent downward trend of inflation figures currently at 9.5
percent, pointed towards better chances of the government to meet
its targets.
</P>
<P>
Manuel discounted recent criticism of the government's Growth,
Employment and Redistribution (GEAR) strategy, saying the targets
of the GEAR were still on track, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, he acknowledged that there was an urgent need to,
among other things, accelerate employment creation as well as to
reverse income and wealth inequalities, which he said was
characteristic of the apartheid economy.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the government is still facing the tough task
of achieving a four percent deficit target after last year's
deficit rose to 5.6 percent of the GDP, defeating earlier
projections in the process, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
