<HEADLINE> Better Phone Service for Scenic City in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Suzhou, in east China's Jiangsu
province, has been modernizing its telecommunications network to
provide better service, according to Wang Jirong, director of the
Bureau of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
It now has computer-controlled switchboards capable of handling
two million lines at once. By the year 2000, there are expected to
be 50 telephone lines per 100 persons, and the city will have
computer-controlled switchboards with a combined handling capacity
of 2.5 million lines.
</P>
<P>
Phone service is available in the city's 1,107 villages, and
there are 15.59 telephones per 100 people in rural areas. Taicang
City, which is under Suzhou's jurisdiction, is China's first
county-level city with telephone service available everywhere.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou Industrial Park, a Sino-Singaporean joint venture, and a
local new development area have caused the city to pay greater
attention to its telecommunications infrastructure for a better
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Switchboards capable of handling 46,000 lines have been
installed for the two development areas. The telecommunications
network for Suzhou Industrial Park is of the highest level,
providing video phone, home PC, and cable TV network services.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu Province has a highly developed rural industry, and
living standards there, especially for villagers, are higher than
many parts of the rest of the country. Suzhou is a
prefecture-level city that used to be referred to as "paradise on
earth". It and Hangzhou, the capital of Zhejiang province, were
known for their uniquely beautiful scenery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization of Banks in Africa Said Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The privatization and
restructuring of banks in Africa in recent years have proved
successful, reports from the on-going first Commonwealth African
banking policy seminar today quoted Kenyan bankers as saying.
</P>
<P>
Executives of two banks in Kenya told the seminar in Mombasa
Wednesday that plans to privatize their banks have led to floated
shares being oversubscribed and the better performance of their
banks.
</P>
<P>
"Having gone public for the last three years, the National
Bank of Kenya (NBK) has continued to record good performance with
impressive growth in profits and assets," NBK Executive Chairman
NBK John Simba said.
</P>
<P>
The financial results of the NBK, the fourth largest bank in
Kenya, recorded an increase of 42.7 percent in 1996 compared with
the previous year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Deposits also increased by 37 percent and these are
indications that the bank has a clear vision in its business,"
Simba said.
</P>
<P>
"A bank changing from state-owned to private-owned needs to
become more market-oriented and customer-focused," he noted.
</P>
<P>
State-owned banks in Africa require detailed transformations
when changing to private ownership and need to streamline their
operation systems, re-package existing and introduce new
products, plus initiating a cultural overhaul, he said.
</P>
<P>
Executive Chairman of the Kenya Commercial Bank (KCB) A. T.
Kaminchia said in a paper presented to the seminar that the
success of the privatization process in his bank was based on the
1996 sale of 11.8 million KCB's governmental shares.
</P>
<P>
"This share issue is important because it satisfied 97 percent
of applicants and it attracted record amounts from foreign
institutional investors," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
