<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Issues Ultimatum to PNA to Quell Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel has issued an ultimatum
to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) demanding an end to
the escalation of Palestinian violence in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
The warning was issued overnight to the PNA by Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai through the Americans.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that Israeli forces would react with an "iron
fist" policy, unless the Palestinian police intervened to quell
the confrontations in Hebron and Gaza Strip,
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Ministry officials also warned that the recent
escalation of Palestinian violence in the West Bank city of
Hebron could jeopardize the efforts to resume the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani also demanded the
Palestinian police to put an end to the violence, otherwise
Israel would change its tactics in dealing with the
stone-throwers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Knesset (Israeli parliament) Wednesday,
Foreign Minister David Levy also urged the PNA to halt the
violence. "It (Israel) can not tolerate such things," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli warning came in the wake of escalation of
Palestinian-Israeli violence in Hebron and Gaza Strip Wednesday,
where Palestinians threw stones and firebombs at Israeli
soldiers, who fired rubber bullets and tear gas in response. Some
reports said Israel deployed snipers on rooftops in Hebron to
shoot Palestinian demonstrators in the legs.
</P>
<P>
At least 38 Palestinians and one Israeli policeman were
injuried in Hebron. Two Israeli soldiers were wounded, one
seriously, in Tuesday's clash in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Clashes also erupted near the Gush Katif settlement in the
Gaza Strip, leading to one Palestinian youth killed and six
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of violence was sparked by the provocative
leaflets posted in Hebron area by a Jewish woman from Jerusalem,
which depicted the Islamic prophet Mohammed as a pig.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli and Palestinian security officials continued
efforts to resume the security cooperation despite the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak held a meeting in
Gaza Wednesday with PNA preventive security chief Mohammed
Dahlan.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security chief in the West Bank Jibril Rajoub
toured Hebron Wednesday, warning that the Hebron situation would
explode if the stalemate in the peace process continued.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian talks have been deadlocked since March
when Israel began building the Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
