<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Urban Population Causes Problems in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Increasing rural Malawians leaving
their rural areas for towns are causing a series of problems such
as malaria.
</P>
<P>
According to a study by the center for Social Research and the
United Nations Children's Fund, Malawi's urban population is
growing by five to 15 percent a year compared with the national
population growth rate of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
This means that 2,000 people are coming to live in the towns
each week and that within the next three years 30 percent of the
population will be in the four major towns of Mzuzu, Lilongwe,
Blantyre and Zomba of the country.
</P>
<P>
The surge to the towns has led to the growth of squatter camps
and caused government concern.
</P>
<P>
The main problem is a lack of basic social amenities such safe
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions have made squatter dwellers prone to a number
of preventable infections such as cholera, diarrhoea and
malaria," said a chief researcher for the study.
</P>
<P>
He also notes that there is also very little access to schools
and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Because there are very few jobs families have been reduced to
begging, prostitution and stealing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
