<HEADLINE> Philippines Urges ASEAN to Attract More Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines today urged the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries to
consolidate themselves economically to attract more investments
inflows.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 4th meeting of ASEAN heads of investment
agencies held here, Philippine Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar
Bautista said the agencies must start working now to strengthen
the region's competitive position on the global market.
</P>
<P>
"While the initial step in our ASEAN borderlessness experience
has been successful in trade, this time around, we should look for
the same success in the field of investments," Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, ASEAN investment agencies can be instrumental
in attracting the types of investments that can serve as vital
tools for bringing economic vitality in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, he said, benefited from growing intra-ASEAN
investments where 31 percent of the total investments from 1991 to
1996 came from ASEAN partners.
</P>
<P>
In the area of trade flows, Bautista said, the country's trade
with ASEAN partners accounted for 12.5 percent in 1996 from 7.7
percent in 1992 in its overall trade worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Economically stronger ASEAN countries must support weaker
economies to enable them to gain strength, become integrated and
benefit from the mainstream of ASEAN economic vitality, Bautista
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
