<HEADLINE> Provisional Urban Council Members Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Fifty members of the Provisional
Urban Council were sworn in here today, the first working day
after the establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
At 8:30 this morning, Dr. Ronald Leung, chairman of the
pre-handover Urban Council, arrived at the Urban Council Chamber
in central district to become the first to pledge his allegiance
to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
With right hand up, he uttered the oath: "I take the office as
member of the Provisional Urban Council upon myself and will duly
and faithfully fulfill the duties of the office according to the
best of my ability." Leung also promised to uphold the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
In the same place, 37 members of the interim body had taken the
oaths of office before 10:15 am today, while 13 had sworn the
oaths in various districts in Hong Kong. All the 50 members were
appointed in June by the HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
As an interim arrangement, the Provisional Urban Council was
formed in order to fill a vacuum in the district organization
since the pre-handover Urban Council ceased to function on June
30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Urban Council consists of no more than 50
members and serves no later than December 31, 1999. The interim
district organization provides municipal services to some 3.3
million people in the urban areas, or half of the population of
Hong Kong. It plays a key role in safeguarding environmental
hygiene and public health, as well as providing cultural programs
and recreational facilities.
</P>
<P>
Following the swearing-in ceremony, all the 50 members cast
secret ballots to elect Dr. Ronald Leung and Ip Kwok Cheung as
chairman and vice chairman of the Provisional Urban Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
