<HEADLINE> Chinese, Kenyan Military Leaders Hold Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- General Fu Quanyou, Chief of the
General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, and his
Kenyan counterpart Daudi Tonje held talks here today.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, they pledged to increase friendship and
cooperation between their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Fu, also a member of the Central Military Commission, said that
China values its time-honored friendship with African nations and
has always supported them in safeguarding independence, their
sovereignty, and destiny. China and Kenya, he added, have had good
cooperation in many areas in recent years, and the leaders of the
two countries have had frequent exchanges of visits. President
Jiang Zemin's visit to Kenya in May of last year was particularly
important to the development of bilateral relations, Fu stressed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his thanks to the Kenyan government for its
adherence to the "One China" policy and its support for China's
reunification.
</P>
<P>
Tonje, who is the first Kenyan military leader to visit China
since the establishment of diplomatic relations in 1963,
congratulated China on the return of Hong Kong, and pointed out
that Kenya's President Daniel Arap Moi has paid three visits to
China.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Fu on Kenya's situation and its foreign and
defense policies, and invited Fu to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Tonje arrived here Wednesday as Fu's guest after attending the
handover ceremony in Hong Kong. 
