<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collapsed Han River Bridge Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A bridge in central Seoul which
collapsed about three years ago was reopened today after 32 months
of rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
The sloppily-constructed Songsu Bridge, located in the eastern
section of the Han River, which runs through the capital,
collapsed in its middle section during morning rush hour on
October 21, 1994, killing 32 and injuring 17 others.
</P>
<P>
The unheard-of disaster served as a major alarm for the country
to weigh the public safety and the economic miracle.
</P>
<P>
In a memorial service with the attendance of the families of
the victims before the reopening ceremony Thursday, Seoul Mayor
Cho Soon vowed to take firm measures to prevent the reoccurrence
of such tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The new bridge, with almost everything replaced except for the
basic structure, is designed to allow heavy vehicles weighing up
to 43.2 tons, an improvement from 32.4 ton level before its
collapse.
</P>
<P>
The reopening of the bridge, with a predicted handling capacity
of about 100,000 vehicles each day, is expected to help ease heavy
traffic at four neighboring bridges.
</P>
<P>
After the collapse of the Songsu bridge, the traffics was
diverted to other neighboring bridges, causing heavy traffic
congestion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
