<HEADLINE> Feature: Refugees in Zambia Longing for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Ngaule Mwambi is extremely
concerned about the new development in his home in Zaire, now the
Democratic Republic of Congo, hoping the vulnerable peace will be
consolidated so that he can return and start a new life there.
</P>
<P>
He said he and his family members are living an unhappy life
in the Meheba Refugee Settlement in the Northwestern Province of
Zambia, 700 kilometers from Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Because of too much rainfall during the last crop season, they
now have not enough food and no money for clothes and blankets as
it is getting cold.
</P>
<P>
Mwambi and 12 other family members fled the bloody tribal
strife in their home town to Zambia in 1994. Mwambi is wondering
what has happened to two of his daughters and their family
members, who failed to flee to Zambia together with him.
</P>
<P>
Meheba Refugee Settlement was established in 1971, mainly for
Angolan refugees fleeing the Angolan liberation war. At its
inception, the settlement had a population of 8,000, while
today's population tops 31,500 comprising various nationalities,
including about 28,000 Angolans, 3,400 Zaireans and 184 Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees are engaged in farming as each family is
allocated 2.5 hectares of land as well as some tools and seeds
upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
Most crops are doing well, particularly maize, cassava, sweet
potatoes, and a variety of vegetables. The refugees sell their
surplus products within and outside the settlement.
</P>
<P>
In the settlement, there are five primary schools, one
secondary school and five clinics set up by the Zambian
government, which also pays the teachers, doctors and nurses it
installed to work there.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the implementation of care and maintenance
programs, some international organizations such as the UNHCR have
completed preparations for repatriation of Angolans and some
16,000 Angolan refugees have expressed their intention to return
this year.
</P>
<P>
All the refugees in the settlement are longing for peace so
that they return. "Here is not our territory, not our homes,"
they answered, when asked if they want to return to their home
country.
</P>
<P>
Old man Kamanda Timotee told Xinhua that 10 of his family
members were killed in the tribal conflict in formerly Zaire and
the survivors fled to Zambia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
A former Zairean university student, Luku George, fled alone
to Zambia in April this year when fierce fightings broke out
between the forces led by Laurent Kabila and Mobutu Sese Seko's
troops.
</P>
<P>
He said he is missing his parents and wants to continue his
study but cannot do so because peace has not been really achieved
in his country. He does not know what to do, complaining there is
nowhere to stay, no job and no alternative but to stay in the
refugee settlement.
</P>
<P>
Angolan refugee Madeus Kahaku is good at agricultural
production and his family lives faily well on what the plot of
land they own can produce. He said although they have a good life
there, they want to return to Angola, build new houses and start
a new life when peace is consolidated.
</P>
<P>
Another Angolan refugee who has been in the settlement for
over 10 years frowned on the word of refugees, saying it is a
"bad word, I don't want the label of refugee. I want to go home
after peace is won."
</P>
<P>
Gahigi Elen, along with her sister and mother fled to Zambia
from Rwanda in 1996. Elen's father is Tutsi while her mother,
Hutu. Her father and other family members of her four brothers
and three sisters were massacred in the ethnic conflicts between
Tutsis and Hutus.
</P>
<P>
She said both tribes consider them alien and try to kill them.
Elen, who is employed in the guest house of the settlement, said
at present she doesn't want to return to her home country,
alleging that killings are still going on there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
