<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Supplementary Feeding to Continue in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
announced that it will continue the multi-million Dollar child
supplementary feeding program despite a bumper harvest realized
this year.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health and Child Welfare Timothy Stamps told a
meeting of donors who help the government fund the program on
Wednesday that at least 416,667 children countrywide would be
given supplementary feeding during the 18-month financial year
which started on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, "the government intends to continue
supplementary feeding in areas affected by localized droughts,
water-logging, pests and crop diseases."
</P>
<P>
He said, "no child should be allowed to suffer from hunger and
malnutrition in Zimbabwe when there is a localized drought just
because in some areas there are bumper harvests."
</P>
<P>
During drought years, the government had been giving rural
children under the age of five daily food supplement.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.2 million children benefited from the program
during the 1995 drought, and another half a million were
registered as beneficiaries during the 1996-97 phase
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the Zimbabwean government and the donor community
had put in 22 million U.S. Dollars into the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
