<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Faces New Challenges: UNDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) has warned that Zimbabwe has a lot to learn from
challenges coming from globalization and competition as its
economy becomes more market-oriented.
</P>
<P>
UNDP resident representative Carlos Lopes said on Wednesday
the world is witnessing remarkable convergence of opinion on
challenges and potential solutions facing decision-maker despite
obvious and continued differences between nations and regions.
</P>
<P>
"As most developing economies, especially those in sub-Saharan
Africa, adopt market-based economic systems, the behavior of
local business entities are increasingly determined and
influenced by events and trends at the global level," he told a
joint Employers Confederation of Zimbabwe and Friedrich Nauman
Foundation seminar on human resources.
</P>
<P>
He said there is now a growing recognition, in both public and
private sectors, of crucial linkages between economic growth,
human development, social cohesion and environmental
sustainability.
</P>
<P>
He added there is equally strong recognition that the new
global challenges could no longer be tackled by rules of
government alone as there is growing importance of the private
sector and good corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, "business leaders, like their political
counterparts, are facing a period of unprecedented change and
complexity. Geo-political transformation and increasing
integration of the world, accompanied by the emergence of new
technologies, markets and competitors are creating threats and
opportunities for business which were unthought of the years
ago." 
</P>
</TEXT>
