<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Calls for Resumption of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A top Philippine government peace
negotiator today called for the resumption of peace talks between
the government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
However, government chief peace negotiator Fortunato Abat said,
the resumption of talks will depend on the decision of the MILF to
return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Speaking over a local radio station, Abat said the peace talks
will only resume if the MILF "calls for it first."
</P>
<P>
He said that it is only logical for the MILF to make the first
move since "it is the one which called-off the negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"The government is only waiting until they are ready," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abat also reiterated that last week's military operations in
the southern provinces of North Cotabato and Maguindanao were not
directed to the MILF but to kidnap-for-ransom groups.
</P>
<P>
The MILF called off the six-round of its low-level peace talks
with the government scheduled for the end of June after the
military launched an all-out assault against it in Central
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Maguidanao Governor Zacaria Candao, a former MILF
leader, said the MILF agreed to talk to him this coming July 5 to
discuss a possible schedule for the resumption of peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to say that the MILF has not changed its position
to continue talking with the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be attended by Ghadzali Jaafar and Al Haj
Murad, MILF vice chairmen for political and military affairs
respectively, and other central committee members.
</P>
<P>
Candao said he will also ask the MILF in their meeting to
cooperate in the government's anti-kidnapping campaign in Central
Mindanao to finally erase doubts on their alleged connections with
lawless elements in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
