<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Opening-up Goes Deeper (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Overseas financial institutions
have become an important component of the Chinese banking system
as financial opening-up goes deeper in China, according to a
senior central bank official.
</P>
<P>
China has made remarkable progress in opening its financial
sector to the rest of the world since it first allowed an overseas
bank to set up a representative office in Beijing in 1979, Chen
Yuan, vice governor of the People's Bank of China, said at a
recent seminar.
</P>
<P>
"To date overseas financial institutions have become an
important part of China's banking system, either in terms of their
number and business scale," he said.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's cabinet, has designated 24 special
economic zones and cities where overseas financial institutions
are allowed to set up operational agencies.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that overseas financial institutions had
established a total of 527 representative offices in China by the
end of last year, which include 288 by overseas banks, 152 by
insurance companies and 53 by securities firms.
</P>
<P>
The number of operational overseas financial institutions in
China reached 156 by the end of 1996, including 131 banks, 11
overseas-funded banks registered in China, five financial
companies, eight insurance companies and one Sino-overseas
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
The 131 overseas banks have been set up by 63 banks in 16
countries and regions. In terms of number of bank branches in
China, Japan led all other countries and regions with 29, followed
by Hong Kong's 25 and France's 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Opening-up Goes Deeper (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, the country's leading economic and commercial center,
has the greatest concentration of overseas bank branches with
37. The special economic zone of Shenzhen, neighboring Hong Kong,
and Guangzhou, capital city of south China's Guangdong Province,
have the second and third largest number of overseas banks, with
24 and 13 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that overseas banks play an important role in making
investment capital from overseas sources available to China's
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the 140 overseas banks operating
at the end of last year had assets totalling 29.9 billion US
dollars, up 56 percent on the previous year. Their outstanding
loans and deposits rose by 53 and 24 percent on a yearly basis to
19.4 billion and 3.9 billion US dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks now account for 3.13 percent of China's total
financial assets and nearly 14.2 percent of the foreign exchange
assets of Chinese financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that overseas banks can generally begin making
profits after their initial two years of operation. Providing
loans to their clients, mainly solid overseas-funded enterprises,
is a low risk business.
</P>
<P>
Post-tax profits of overseas banks jumped 31 percent last year
to 183 million US dollars, according to official statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
