<HEADLINE> South-South Mayors Conference Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A four-day South-South Mayors
Conference opened here today to develop solutions for the cities
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
About 300 city leaders and planners from countries in the South
are attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition on quality urban life is being held alongside the
conference with more than 120 companies from 13 countries taking
part.
</P>
<P>
Officiating the conference, Malaysia's acting Prime Minister
Anwar Ibrahim highlighted the daunting challenge of nurturing
caring cities in his opening address.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the mayors from South-South countries is to
prevent cities in the South from growing into "brutal, cold and
menacing" metropolises, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
A city must be geared to meet the needs of the teeming
multitude rather than the privileged few, he said, adding that
thus education and health care for all, public housing, public
transportation, public recreational facilities must take
precedence.
</P>
<P>
He said the re-greening of cities today was not only for beauty
sake but has become a matter of psychological necessity.
</P>
<P>
He said "to bring nature into city and creating city within a
garden will restore man's relationship with nature and create the
ambiance for the renewal of human society."
</P>
<P>
"We must take our cities into the frontier of technological
discovery. We must discard the attitude of merely trying to catch
up with cities in the North," he said.  
</P>
