<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Gainers, Losers From Baht Floatation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- There will be gainers and losers
after the government put into force the decision to float the Thai
currency on July 2.
</P>
<P>
The floatation will lead to devaluation of the baht and will
first of all benefit Thai exporters of agricultural products and
other goods with low import content.
</P>
<P>
Thai businesses investing overseas will bring home more money
in terms of the baht.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors may find investment in Thailand less costly
and more profitable because of the floated exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry will gain as foreign tourists will find
Thailand a cheaper destination to visit as their currency will
exchange for more Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
However, Thai importers will have to pay more for their
purchases from abroad: industries heavily reliant on imported raw
materials, goods and capital will suffer as they must pay more in
terms of baht.
</P>
<P>
As Thailand will pay an estimated 700 million US dollars more
for imported petroleum this year, big users of energy are bound to
have more bills to pay.
</P>
<P>
Firms with high unhedged foreign loan exposure are likely to
face severe repayment problems as costs soar in the wake of the
baht's managed float. In this aspect, the Thai private sector has
about 60-80 billion dollars or the equivalent outstanding in
foreign currency loans, with many unhedged against currency
fluctuations after years of the baht being virtually fixed by the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors in Thailand repatriating profits abroad will
have to pay more for the foreign currency they buy.
</P>
<P>
Thai people will think twice before they book air tickets for
overseas trips, as they will have to pay more because of the
weaker baht.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya said Thailand will gain in the
long run as the baht floatation would mean a healthier economy and
more cash would flow into the country.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating, he said that in the past when the US dollar was
weak, Thailand, which had pegged its exchange rate system to the
basket of currencies largely dominated by the dollar, benefited as
foreign investors were attracted to set up production bases in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
However, lately the baht appreciated when the dollar
strengthened against other major currencies, slowing capital
inflow into Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
