<HEADLINE> India's Cotton Textiles Exports up By 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 3 (Xinhua)-- India's export of cotton textiles
registered a 20 percent increase in US dollar terms during the
first two months of the current financial year starting April 1
over the same period of the previous year, official sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
And textiles exports between January and May this year rose by
29 percent, touching 55.86 billion rupees (1.574 billion US
dollars) against 43.26 billion rupees (1.22 billion US dollars)
recorded in the previous corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, cotton yarn export, which has been witnessing a
buoyant trend since the last three years, increased by more than
50 percent during January-May and accounted for 47 percent of the
cotton textiles exports, which include fabrics, sewing thread and
made-ups.
</P>
<P>
Exports of cotton made-ups comprised 21 percent of the total
cotton textiles export and it went up from 9.83 billion rupees
(276.90 million US dollars) to 11.97 billion rupees (337.18
million US dollars) during the first five months of the annual
year.
</P>
<P>
Cotton fabrics exports also rose by 13 percent during the first
two months of the current financial year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
