<HEADLINE> India Government to Go Ahead With Wheat Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government would go
ahead with the import of contracted wheat despite high estimates
for domestic output during the 1996-97 crop year, Agriculture
Ministry sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Although over one million tonnes of wheat have arrived in the
country, it has been decided to import the targeted two million
tonnes of wheat. The priority of the government is to ensure
abundance foodgrain stock in the country.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Chaturanan Mishra has made it clear that
the government would not hesitate to think in terms of import of
wheat during 1997-98 if it was confronted with the problem of
black marketing and hoarding.
</P>
<P>
Although there would be no need to import wheat this year to
help sustain the public distribution system, the government could
still import wheat if market prices were manipulated beyond
reasonable levels, the minister has said.
</P>
<P>
India's wheat production stood at 65.77 million tonnes during
1994-95, but declined to 62.62 million tonnes during 1995-96,
which was one of the major factors for the government decision on
wheat imports, the same sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
