<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KEDO to Start Building Nuclear Reactors for DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization (KEDO) today signed an agreement in New York, giving
the go-ahead to the building of two nuclear reactors in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was the culmination of two years of negotiations
between the DPRK and KEDO following a 4.5 billion U.S.-dollar
framework agreement signed in Geneva in 1994 between Washington
and Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
Under today's agreement, KEDO, an international consortium
based in New York, is providing two 1,000-megawatt light-water
nuclear reactors in exchange for a pledge by the DPRK to freeze
its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
The project is to be started in August and is expected to be
completed by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will bear most of the cost of the project, now
estimated at some 5 billion dollars, KEDO officials said.
</P>
<P>
Executive director of the consortium, Stephen Bosworth, said
the agreement resolved technical details about the project, such
as transport, labor, customs, communications, medical and
financial services.
</P>
<P>
Working out the practical arrangements has been difficult
because the project is not only commercially complicated, but also
politically sensitive, Bosworth said.
</P>
<P>
KEDO was established in 1995 in New York to implement the 1994
framework agreement between the DPRK and the United
States. Members of KEDO include the United States, South Korea,
Japan, Australia, New Zealand, Canada and some European Union
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
