<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Baht's Value Plunges After Allowed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- After the Thai central bank's
announcement on Wednesday morning to allow the Thai currency to
float, the baht's value plunged from about 26 baht to the US
dollar on Monday, to 30.36 baht at its peak on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local baht trading was volatile, with many banks suspending
trade because of the lack of a benchmark midrate, which had been
fixed on a day-to-day basis by the central bank until June 30.
</P>
<P>
Some commercial banks quoted the baht at 29.80 per dollar, down
about 15 percent in value, before easing to 27.50.
</P>
<P>
Chaos reigned in some banks, where tellers refused to exchange
baht for foreign currency while tourists fumed.
</P>
<P>
The currency is expected to swing wildly for a few days, but
the authorities are banking on a cheaper baht to stimulate
exports, along with a return of investor confidence in an economy
that analysts said "had lost its way".
</P>
<P>
The decision on a "managed float" of the baht came after the
prime minister and the Bank of Thailand had repeatedly insisted
that the baht would not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand had spent about 6 billion dollars out of
its 39 billion dollars in foreign exchange reserves in recent
months to defend the currency against speculators.
</P>
<P>
The decision to let the baht move with real market forces put
an end to the 13-year-old exchange rate system, in which the baht
was pegged to the basket of currencies dominated by the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
Although a "managed float" is not a devaluation, the baht has
depreciated strongly on the first day of the baht seeking its real
value.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, investors welcomed the baht devaluation, with the
Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index rose 41.51 points, or 7.8
percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Defending the new move, Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
said, "we have been through the illusion for far too long. Now we
must adjust to reality."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
