<HEADLINE> More Fossils Collected in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- More fossils, which were found in
Myanmar by four individuals, have been handed to the authorities
for paleontologists to study, official paper The New Light of
Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The fossils included modern age elephant molar, crocodile bone,
mammal leg bone, ox molars, goat lower jaw and molar and turtle's
shell.
</P>
<P>
Experts at home and abroad are being encouraged and supported
by the government for exploration of fossils to link up the
history of Myanmar, disclosed Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General
Khin Nyunt who received the donations here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt, who is first secretary of the Myanmar State Law and
Order Restoration Council, also disclosed that the experts have
already discovered evidence that Stone Age human beings lived in
Myanmar and there also existed creatures in the country prior to
the period of humans.
</P>
<P>
Experts of Myanmar universities discovered pieces of fossilized
remains of a primate in Pondaung area in Sagaing division,
northwest of the country, in March-April this year.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar experts said that the discovery in Pondaung belongs
to 40-million-year-old formation, a higher primate helpful for
tracing the origin of anthropoids, according to earlier official
report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
