<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Cuts 1.35 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The El Nino-driven pattern of
widespread dry weather could set back the pace of economic growth
in the financial year of 1997-1998, with a projected cost so far
of 1.35 billion US dollars, it was reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource
Economics (ABARE), El Nino would lead to a slump in crop yields
and production, accounting for a fall of almost 1.35 billion US
dollars in crop values.
</P>
<P>
The current El Nino pattern was similar to that experienced
during the 1982 drought, which reduced the country's gross
domestic product by 2 percent, a leading weather forecaster told
the national newspaper The Australian yesterday.
</P>
<P>
While winter crop plantings remain high despite dry conditions,
ABARE forecasted overall production levels in the financial year
of 1997-1998, which started on July 1, 1997, will be well down on
the record set in 1996-1997 with average wheat yields down by 29
percent.
</P>
<P>
The new official forecast for the rural sector will undermine
the budget prediction of 3.75 percent economic growth for 1997-98,
which assumed farm output growth based on "normal seasonal
conditions".
</P>
<P>
In its Australian Crop Report, published yesterday, ABARE said
the plantings would "remain historically high" at just over 18
million hectares in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
"A major factor contributing to this is the expectation of high
grain and oilseed prices in 1997-98 relative to the expected
returns for wool and beef," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said the extended spell of dry weather would hit
most crops across the country.
</P>
<P>
Production levels of wheat, barley and oats were expected to be
down in each mainland state and yields were forecast to fall below
the five-year averages for those crops.
</P>
<P>
Bill Kininmonth, head of Australia's National Climate Center,
said there was a high likelihood of "significantly below average
rainfall" for the southern and south-west Queensland, southern New
South Wales (NSW), Victoria, south Australia and Tasmania states.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of NSW, 10 percent of Queensland and
Gippsland, Victoria was declared drought-affected.
</P>
<P>
He said the current El Nino had "all he characteristics" of the
1982 drought.
</P>
<P>
El Nino refers to changes in temperature across the Pacific
Ocean, measured by the South Oscillation Index (SOI), the
difference in air pressure between Tahiti and Darwin. A low SOI
means drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Newspaper Hails Hong Kong's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's peaceful return to
China is a symbol of the success of the Chinese revolutionary
process, a Nicaraguan newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The "Barricada" paper dedicated a whole page to articles on
China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong
on July 1.
</P>
<P>
An article written by Augusto Zamora said that 156 years of
British rule came to an end with the transition of power over Hong
Kong to a powerful and revived China, led with a firm hand by the
Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
It said Hong Kong's return to its motherland closed an era of
imperialism and colonial rule in Asia by the West, and marked the
beginning of a new era, during which Asia will become the center of
the world economy with "China as one of its epicenters."
</P>
<P>
Another article carried in the paper, with the headline of
"China's Big Strategic Objective", said Hong Kong's handover
marked the ending of China's most humiliating period, and the
rebirth of the nation.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese communists knew how to position China in the
world's vanguard. This is well proved by the fact that China had
Mao as one of the greatest leaders in its thousand-year
history .... Hong Kong will be the symbol of this success," the
article concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
