<HEADLINE> Highly-Indebted Countries Hold Meeting in Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Four highly-indebted Latin
American countries gathered here today to set up a Poor Countries
Club as a counterweight to the European-based Paris Club group of
creditors.
</P>
<P>
The initiative to set up the club was proposed by World Bank
representatives in 1996 to help highly-indebted poor
countries. The club will make proposals as a bloc to international
credit organizations about retiring or forgiving member countries'
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental officials from Bolivia, Nicaragua, Guyana and
Honduras attended the meeting which was sponsored by European
development organizations for Latin America and the Latin American
Episcopal Council.
</P>
<P>
Honduran President Carlos Alberto Reina opened the first
session of the meeting to form the club.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the Honduran president praised the efforts made
by Latin American non-governmental organizations to come up with
mechanisms to reduce the high debts of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that another 37 countries on other continents are
facing similar problems due to high late-interest payments which
make repayment impossible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
