<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Begins Underground Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States today began a
round of controversial underground nuclear weapons-related tests
in the Nevada desert, an Energy Department spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
In the subcritical experiments, code-named "REBOUND", a total
of 73 kg of chemicals were exploded in a tunnel 293 meters
underground, to measure the impact on plutonium under high
pressure, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Last week, 44 U.S. congressmen wrote to U.S. President Bill
Clinton, urging him to stop the experiments.
</P>
<P>
They said that the move violated the spirit of the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty, signed last year by nuclear
powers, including the United States, to outlaw all types of
nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. administration argued that it was not violating
the the treaty and said the tests, which involve massive
supercomputer calculations, were needed to assess how age would
affect materials in the U.S. nuclear arsenal and predict weapons
performance without actual explosions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., which conducted its last nuclear weapons explosion in
1992, will conduct another test later this year and four more next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Trade Deficit Soars in First Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's trade deficit
soared to 4.7 billion U.S. dollars in the first six months, or 85
percent of the 1996 total.
</P>
<P>
Statistics published on Tuesday by the Ministry of Industry,
Commerce and Tourism said that exports for the period totaled
24.78 billion dollars and imports 29.49 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that the trade deficit for the whole year
may reach 11 billion dollars against last year's 5.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's trade deficit has been on the rise since July 1994
when the government took measures to encourage imports and
restrict exports in order to curb inflation.
</P>
<P>
Recently, however, the government decided to boost exports to
cut down trade deficit but has made no notable achievements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
