<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Bailey Beaten in Lausanne GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Maurice Greene, fresh from winning
the American national men's 100-meter title, edged Olympic
champion Donovan Bailey of Canada in the event at the Lausanne
Grand Prix Athletics tournament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite pouring rain at the Lausanne grand prix meeting, Greene
stormed back in the final 10 meters to hold off Olympic silver
medallist Frankie Fredericks and Bailey and win in 9.90 seconds,
equalling his own second-fastest time in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks had to settle for the second only one hundreth of a
second behind with Bailey third in 9.97.
</P>
<P>
Britain's former world and Olympic champion Linford Christie
could manage only seventh in 10.12.
</P>
<P>
The field was one of the fastest in the international
tournaments as six of the eight sprinters had run under 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
World and Olympic high-hurdles champion Allen Johnson also
overcame the bad weather condition to clock the fastest time in
the world this year in the men's 110 meters hurdles with 13.17
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Despite striking the third hurdle from the finish, Johnson
powered through to win ahead of American Olympic silver medallist
Mark Crear at 13.21 and Cuban Anier Garcia, 13.27. Britain's
world record holder Colin Jackson was fourth in 13.28.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Olympic champion Ludmila Engquist also clocked an
impressive 12.65 seconds for the women's 100 metres hurdles, the
second-fastest time of the season.
</P>
<P>
American Suzy Hamilton scored a season world best in the
women's mile of four minutes 26.01 seconds. But the time was a
long way short of the world mark of 4:12.56 held by Russian
Svetlana Masterkova. 
</P>
</TEXT>
