<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Welcomes Talks on Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia welcomed every effort to
resume the dialogue between the governments of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and South Korea in a bid to
solve differences, an official said.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome every positive step toward peace in the region,"
Political Affairs Director General of the Indonesian Foreign
Ministry Nugroho Wisnumurti here Wednesday told a seminar on Korea
and Southeast Asia in the 21st century, sources at the seminar
said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reports said the negotiations between the two sides
will be resumed in August 5 this year.
</P>
<P>
The condition in the Korean peninsula, Nugroho believed, could
not be separated from stability in the wider Asia Pacific region,
and therefore has the potential to effect developments in the
Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia and other non-aligned countries are concerned
over the development of the nuclear issue in the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we hope that the four-party talks should be
convened, and will hopefully become a turning point from the
current situation there," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that ASEAN's (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
achievements in the political, security, economic and social
fields could not have been as successful as they are without
support from the two countries (DPRK and South Korea).
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Issue Rules on Partnerships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to move ahead with its plan to requite large companies to
form partnerships with small and medium companies and
cooperatives, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto had ordered the Ministry of Cooperatives and
Small Enterprises and related agencies to prepare a regulation to
encourage the partnerships, Coordinating Minister for Production
and Distribution Hartarto said here last night.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry and related agencies are working on the criteria
for the obligation of large companies to help small businesses,"
Hartarto said after the cabinet meeting on poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
He quoted President Soeharto, who chaired the meeting, as
saying partnerships were needed to boost the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has been promoting linkage between
large and small firms as part of its poverty alleviation policy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Soeharto launched the Jimbaran group, a gathering of
41 tycoons, which aims to develop programs to help small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia at present has 22 million poor people, or 11 percent
of the country's total population, and every year the number is
aimed to go down by at least two percent.
</P>
<P>
The government is resolved to fully eradicate poverty by the
end of the 7th Five-Year Development Plan (1999-2004), officials
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
