<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Repairs in Southwest China Near Completion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Reconstruction work in Lijiang
Prefecture in southwest China's Yunnan Province, which was hit by
an earthquake measuring seven on the Richter Scale in February of
last year, is nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
The quake killed 322 people, injured 3,700 and caused losses
worth five billion yuan (60 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
China planned to completely rebuild the region within three
years, but Lijiang has already completed 80 percent of the planned
reconstruction projects in a little over a year. A total of 924
million yuan has been spent on the work, which included rebuilding
houses, schools, hospitals, highways, water and power supplies,
and telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<P>
Most of the areas 64,442 households are living in brand new or
rebuilt housing.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has also recovered quickly, and tourist accommodation
grew by 550 beds to 1,850. More than 600,000 Chinese and overseas
tourists had visited Lijiang by the end of May. Lijiang's
attractions include sub-tropical vegetation, beautiful scenery,
and colorful local ethnic minority groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
