<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Backs Romania's NATO Membership Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said
today that Bonn would support Romania's bid to join the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) soon.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said, "he and the German government are considering with
much sympathy and give their support to Romania's wish to soon
integrate into NATO," said government spokesman Peter Hausmann.
</P>
<P>
The chancellor held talk here today with visiting Romanian
President Emil Constantinescu on Bucharest's bid to join the
Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Kohl confirmed that a consensus by all 16
existing NATO members was necessary to open to the door to Romania
at the upcoming NATO summit in Madrid which starts on July 8,
Hausmann said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has made clear its intention to invite only
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary to join the NATO in the
first wave. But most of the European Union member states including
France and Italy also want to see Romania and Slovenia to join the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
German newspapers said it is unlikely for Romania to join NATO
in the first wave and the Romanian president's one-day working
visit to Bonn was aimed at seeking support for its NATO membership
at the second stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
