<HEADLINE> Tibet's Economy Sees Stable Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in the Tibet
Autonomous Region in southwest China has been stable since the
start of the year, with industrial output for the January-May
period rising eight percent over the same period last year to 400
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in the region also rose eight percent during the
period to 1.4 billion yuan. The retail price index and consumer
price index rose 5.1 percent and 6.5 percent respectively during
the five-month period over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Local officials express confidence in this year's harvest and
in animal husbandry. Improved use of scientific measures has
pushed the survival rate of lambs and calves up 14.9 percentage
points over the corresponding January-May period of last year, and
deaths of adult livestock dropped 4.7 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
