<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Pollution Getting Trashed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's railways in the last year
have picked up some 20,000 tons of plastic fast food containers
and other wastes discarded by passengers along the nation's more
than 60,000 kilometers of rail lines, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
Officials said volunteers and railway workers have cleaned
about half of the rail lines.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways and several other related government
ministries a few years ago began a national campaign to end the
so-called "white pollution," once a serious problem along railways
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see that the problem is being successfully
alleviated and promise further geared-up efforts on the rest of
the railway sections," said Ding Qingxue, a Railway Ministry
official in charge of cleaning up the pollution.
</P>
<P>
Besides persistent publicity and education to raise the
awareness of the public, Ding said his ministry has since 1994
operated clean-up campaigns, "gathering waste food containers in
trains, organizing rail staff and volunteers to collect discharged
food containers, and replacing non-biodegradable plastic
containers with biodegradable ones made of paper or plastics."
</P>
<P>
"Today, fewer and fewer train passengers throw their used food
containers and other trash out of the windows. Instead, more and
more people conscientiously put the rubbish into trash bags
prepared on the trains," Ding said yesterday in an interview with
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that 150,000 tons of waste were released by
passenger trains in China a year, including about 400 million
plastic containers for fast food sold on trains.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the food containers were thrown along the
railways without being treated. The non-biodegradable containers,
together with plastic instant noodle bowls and other plastic
packages, have been an eyesore in railway stations and along rail
lines.
</P>
<P>
Most railway stations in China have managed to clean up the
waste daily, and sanitation work has been exceptionally good in
major hubs such as Guangzhou and Zhengzhou, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more than 2 million people have been organized
nationwide annually to clean the waste along the railways,
collecting an average of 20,000 tons each year.
</P>
<P>
Trash bags are also available on more and more passenger
trains, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Since July 1 last year, biodegradable food containers have been
introduced on all passenger trains to replace the
non-biodegradable plastic containers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
