<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Treasurer Peter Costello seized on good economic figures
yesterday to promise a "benign interest-rate climate" and stronger
economic growth in an apparent bid to boost flagging business
confidence.
</P>
<P>
He explained a favorable budget assessment from US ratings
agency Moody's, the biggest monthly rise in retail sales for six
years and a lift in building approvals made it a "good news for
the Australian economy".
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- New South Wales government agencies have known for nearly 20
years that drums of dioxin-contaminated waste are buried at the
Homebush site near where major Olympics venues are now being
built, including the athletes village.
</P>
<P>
The state government last month unveiled a plan to clean up the
site before the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard has held out the prospect of big
income tax cuts for low to middle-income earners as a result of
tax reform.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Internet trading may be costing Australian retailers and the
government up to 1.5 billion US dollars a year in lost sales and
uncollected taxes, according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
The figures could rise dramatically if authorities adopt US
President Bill Clinton's proposal, launched yesterday, to
establish a global free-trade zone on the Internet. 
</P>
