<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Girl Storms into Wimbledon Quarterfinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Martina Hingis of
Switzerland, third seed Jana Novotna of Czech Republic and Spanish
tennis veteran Aranxta Sanchez Vicario have cruised into the
Wimbledon semi-finals. But it is Russian teenager Anna Kournikova
who stole the limelight by becoming a surprise semi-finalist.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Russian girl disposed of French Open Champion
Iva Majoli of Croatia in straight sets 7-6 6-4, paving the way for
a spectacular semi-final clash with world number one Hingis, who
trounced Denisa Chladkova of the Czech Republic 6-3 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova, ranked 42 in the world, battled her way into the
last eight by beating 7-seeded German player Anke Huber and
doubles expert Helena Sukova in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the coming battle with Kournikova, a confident
Hingis, only nine months older than her opponent, said: "She's a
different player on grass and she is much better here."
</P>
<P>
"Until now I always have beaten her pretty easily," a smiling
Hingis added.
</P>
<P>
In another women's singles semi-final match, Novotna will take
on Sanchez Vicario to fight for the other semi-final position. The
two tennis veterans, both once Wimbledon finalists, are expected
to go all out in collecting a precious Wimbledon trophy.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles events, British player Tim Henman, 14th
seed, created the most dramatic upset by knocking the defending
Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands out of the most well-known
tennis championships in a fierce battle 7:6 6:7 7:6 6:4.
</P>
<P>
In another men's singles clash, world number one Pete Sampras
of the United States moved with obvious difficulties into the last
eight after defeating 16-seeded Czech player Petro Korda in
five-sets 6-4 6-3 6-7 6-7 6-7.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the match, Sampras said: "I could have made it a
lot easier on myself. It just goes to show that if you get a
little careless, all of a sudden he's back in the match."
</P>
<P>
On his semi-final battle with German veteran Boris Backer, also
three-times Wimbledon winner, Sampras said: "It doesn't get
easier. Boris and I have had some unbelievable matches over the
years and hopefully we can play some great tennis tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to walk into it like a final. He has a presence that
not too many players have," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
