<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six IRA Men Jailed 35 Years Each for Plotting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Six IRA men were sentenced for 35
years each today for plotting to bomb London electric power
stations, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said the six activists were convicted of conspiracy
to cause explosions likely to endanger life.
</P>
<P>
They were charged of plotting to bomb electricity stations and
paralyze power supplies to London and south-eastern England in
1996 to humiliate the British government for its rule in the
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said six bombs were to be attached to
transformers at each of the six electricity power stations ringing
London in what the IRA had intended to be its biggest operation
since the end of its 17-month ceasefire six months previously in
February 1996.
</P>
<P>
The gang was arrested in London in July 1996 after a
surveillance operation by police and secret service agents as the
activists prepared for a practice run.
</P>
<P>
The defendants, however, had denied the charges, claiming they
were merely planning a hoax to force British authorities to shut
down electricity supplies themselves, and cause chaos in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Hanratty, a self-confessed IRA activist, said the IRA
had intended to bring more chaos to London than at any time since
the Blitz during World War Two.
</P>
<P>
"The electrical impact would be total disruption in London. All
the traffic lights would be out. It would result in chaos. All
industries would be starved -- rail, tube and travel," Hanratty
told the court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls on Arab Countries to Attend Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Wednesday
called on Arab countries not to boycott a regional economic summit
to be held in Qatar in November after Saudi Arabia had said it
would not attend the meeting because of Israel's participation.
</P>
<P>
"We encourage all Arab countries to participate in the Doha
economic summit. Those Arab governments who said they won't
attend, we hope they'ss reconsider their positions," State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as Saudi Arabia's Crown Prince Abdullah said
in a article, published on Monday, that his country would not
attend the Doha summit and advised Qatar to cancel it.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said on Tuesday that his
country had not yet decided whether to attend the meeting. Egypt
hosted the gathering last year.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process is now in an impasse as the
Israelis insisted in keeping on with their housing construction in
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem in spite of strong opposition
from Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Qatar said on Wednesday that it was going ahead with
preparations for the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
