<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Pound Rallies Sharply, Pulling Dollar up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell to a
six-month low against the British pound but ended mostly stronger
in other foreign-exchange dealings Wednesday, indirectly pulled
higher by a powerful rally in the British currency.
</P>
<P>
Many said it was increasingly likely that the Bank of England
would raise interest rates at its policy-making meeting next week.
Rising rates in Britain have been a major force propelling the
pound higher.
</P>
<P>
The dollar reached an intraday high of 1.7550 marks, its fourth
straight high against the German currency since February, 1994,
before settling in New York at 1.7536 marks, up from 1.7467
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar cost 114.49 yen, down from 114.88 yen. The pound
cost 1.6731 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6581 U.S. dollars and the
highest level since January 16.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday: 1.4700
Swiss francs, up from 1.4653; 5.9040 French francs, up from 5.8845;
1,705.00 Italian lire, up from 1,700.50; 1.3774 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.3790.  
</P>
</TEXT>
