<DOCNO> XIE19970703.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garlic Helps Keep Heart Healthy, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Garlic can do more than just ward
off vampires, it can help keep your heart healthy, according to a
study reported at a cardiology conference in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
A German clinical trial found that people who take daily garlic
supplements have more flexibility in their major blood vessels and
a lower incidence of heart disease than those who don't take
garlic or use it in cooking.
</P>
<P>
"The effect is very striking," Dr. Gustav Belz, a German
cardiologist, was quoted as saying by the Globe and Mail newspaper
today.
</P>
<P>
Stiffening of the vessel walls, a condition called
arteriosclerosis, makes blood flow less freely and puts a greater
load on the heart. Stiffening occurs naturally with age.
</P>
<P>
Yet, people who take garlic can slow the hardening process by
20 percent. "The effect is like delaying by years the stiffening
that comes with aging," Dr. Belz said.
</P>
<P>
He said this is the first study to look at garlic's effect on
the arteries. Previous research has shown garlic can lower
cholesterol and blood pressure and this could explain part of the
result.
</P>
<P>
He believes that garlic could reduce the rate of blood
clotting, which is a factor in the buildup of blockages on the
inside of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
The 202 Germans in the study were between the ages of 50 and
80. Half took daily supplements in the form of garlic powder
tablet and their results were compared with the other half who had
similar diets but didn't take garlic.
</P>
<P>
The garlic users taking 600 to 900 mg a day had an average
reduction in serum cholesterol of 12 percent. And this was
estimated to have lowered their overall risk of heart attack by an
equal percentage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
