<HEADLINE> Dow Close to Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rallied to new
highs today after the Federal Reserve confirmed expectations by
not raising interest rates to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 73.05 points to
7,795.38, ending about a point shy of June 20's record high.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1
margin, with volume totaling 526.78 million shares as against
539.41 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures rose enough to close at new highs.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list added 13.01 points to
904.04, closing above the 900-mark for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Also setting new highs were the NYSE composite index, up 5.70
to 471.71; and the Nasdaq composite, up 17.37 to 1,455.62. The
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.45 to 630.06, just
0.04 shy of record territory.
</P>
<P>
While the stock market was mostly higher since the open, the
Dow had been trading slightly lower until Fed officials concluded
a two-day strategy meeting with no change in the central bank's
key lending rates.
</P>
<P>
In the latest suggestion that the robust U.S. economy may be
slowing enough to ease inflationary pressures without a Fed rate
hike, the Commerce Department reported this morning that orders to
U.S. factories fell a bigger-than-anticipated 0.7 percent in May.
On Tuesday, blue-chip shares rose amid similarly mild readings on
factory activity and construction spending.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
